<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Seattle Signs Its No. 1 Draft Choice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Mariners on Sunday announced they  
signed high school catcher Ryan Christianson, their first-round 
pick and the 11th overall selection in last month's baseball draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Christianson, 18, from Arlington High School in Riverside,  
Calif., will report to the Mariners' rookie league team in Peoria, 
Ariz. If he plays well there, he could be elevated to Class A 
Everett of the Northwest League in ``a couple of weeks,'' said 
Frank Mattox, the team's director of scouting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our plan is to get him going in Peoria,'' Mattox said at a  
news conference. ``The main thing now is to get him playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Reynolds, Christianson's agent, said his client signed a  
standard minor-league contract with a signing bonus, but neither he 
nor Mattox would reveal its terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``After three years hopefully, he'll be good enough where the  
Mariners want to put him on their 40-man roster,'' Reynolds said. 
</P>
<P>
	Christianson is a 6-foot-2, 210-pounder who is a right-handed  
hitter. He batted .514 (38-for-74) with eight homers and 40 RBIs in 
his senior high school season, helping his team post a 29-2 record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'll be a little bit disappointed if I'm not up here  
in at least four years,'' Christianson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
