<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy Search Dominates World News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The disappearance of John F. Kennedy Jr. after his  
plane crashed into the Atlantic Ocean grabbed headlines across the 
world on Sunday as people waited for the search's results. 
</P>
<P>
	British newspapers were dominated by news of the search for  
Kennedy, his wife and her sister, many of the stories focusing on 
the history of tragedy that has plagued America's most famous 
political family. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inexplicable curse of the Kennedys,'' The Sunday Telegraph  
newspaper said in a headline for a story that ran over three pages. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy was traveling with his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy,  
and sister-in-law, Lauren Bessette, to a family wedding when their 
plane disappeared Friday night on its way to Martha's Vineyard, 
Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, the British Broadcasting Corp. led its early morning  
radio news Sunday with a report of the plane's disappearance, while 
the BBC's Internet site said the Kennedy family ``could be facing 
another tragedy, the latest in a long history which has become 
known as the curse of the Kennedys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In France, ``Le Journal du Dimanche'' devoted its front page to  
Kennedy, with the headline: ``The Kennedy Tragedy.'' The paper 
filled two full pages with stories and photos about the late 
president's son and his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	The reaction was similar in Hong Kong. ``The Kennedy family  
again meets the vicious curse,'' ran the headline of the 
Chinese-language daily Oriental Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	In China, the state-run Liberation Daily newspaper of Shanghai  
said Kennedy's disappearance further covers the Kennedy family 
``with a mysterious shade of tragedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's acting prime minister, Tim Fischer, sent a message  
of sympathy to the Kennedy family. 
</P>
<P>
	Cambodians, however, were far more concerned with the murder of  
one of their own national icons, actress Piseth Peaklica. More than 
10,000 people packed her funeral Sunday, some spending their life 
savings to get there. 
</P>
<P>
	Kong Korm, a senator, said that ``politicians might hear about  
the crash, but I doubt regular Cambodians are interested because it 
is too far from them to care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italian state TV led with the Kennedy story, using the  
well-known 1963 photograph of ``John-John,'' as Kennedy is known, 
saluting his father's coffin. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Frankfurter Allgemeine on Sunday featured the same  
photo on its front page with a headline: ``Tragedy without end: 
John F. Kennedy Jr. Crashes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Russia, the independent NTV television carried news of the  
search, accompanied by footage of Kennedy meeting President 
Clinton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
