<DOCNO> APW19990718.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 09:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Armstrong Maintain Cycling Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAINT-GAUDENS, France (AP) -- Lance Armstrong remained in command  
of the Tour de France on Sunday, with Russia's Dimitri Konyshev 
winning the 14th stage as riders reached the foothills of the 
Pyrenees. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong finished in 61st place but retained the yellow jersey  
he has worn the past week. He leads cycling's most famous race by 7 
minutes, 44 second. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, riding for U.S. Postal Service, won the Tour's  
prologue July 3, a time trial and a grueling mountain stage in the 
Alps. The Texan has staged a remarkable recovery from testicular 
cancer and is the overwhelming favorite to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Konyshev, riding for Mercatone, was followed by two Italians --  
Gianni Faresin of the Mapei team and Massimilliano Lelli of 
Cofidis. 
</P>
<P>
	The race followed the pattern of the previous three days, with  
the overall leaders some 15 minutes behind, economizing their 
energy. 
</P>
<P>
	The results had no impact on the top of the overall standings  
since none of the top three stage winners was among the top 30 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The 124-mile stage between Castres and Saint-Gaudens marked the  
final day of relatively flat racing before next week's potentially 
decisive climbs in the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	The stage began in hot, muggy weather but showers midway through  
brought some relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday is the second rest day of the race. The Tour de France  
ends July 25 in Paris on the famed Champs-Elysees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 23:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tragedy Marks White House Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A White House dinner for Israeli Prime  
Minister Ehud Barak was marked by optimistic talk Sunday night of 
peace in the Middle East, but a tragedy of another kind cast a 
cloud that no one could ignore. 
</P>
<P>
	``This a good day for affirming the eternal friendship between  
Israel and the United States,'' said President Clinton to the 400 
guests. ``It is also a hard day for those of use who are 
Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Clinton spoke, U.S. Coast Guard officials were confirming  
what almost everyone feared -- that in all likelihood John F. 
Kennedy Jr., his wife and his sister-in-law perished when their 
small plane apparently crashed into the waters near Martha 
Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are reminded again that life and its possibilities are  
fleeting, that we mortals are obliged to be humble and grateful for 
every day and to make the most of every day,'' said Clinton, 
alluding to the loss of Kennedy in the prime of his life. 
</P>
<P>
	``We share America's sorrow tonight,'' said Barak.  
</P>
<P>
	Although not an official state dinner, it was among the biggest  
for a visiting dignitary, twice as large a normal state dinner. The 
400 guests took 2 1/2 hours to snake through the receiving line. Mrs. 
Clinton, aware that many of the guests were from New York where she 
is likely to pursue a Senate campaign, kept her smile throughout. 
She knew many of the guests personally and greeted them 
emotionally. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the size of the guest list, the dinner was held in a  
massive tent on the South Lawn. As Clinton and Barak began their 
toasts, the president told the guests to ``relax because our 
speeches will be only half a long as the receiving line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The guests included Leah Rabin, the widow of the late Israeli  
prime minister who was killed by an assassin. Clinton gave her a 
big embrace, as did Barak as she went through the line. 
</P>
<P>
	It was about an hour into the line, when Henry Kissinger, the  
former secretary of state, flanked in front by Sen. Patrick Leahy, 
D-Vt., and in back by Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., made it to the 
president and prime minister. And an additional 30 minutes passed 
before Colin Powell, former chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, 
appeared. 
</P>
<P>
	The receiving line went into brief disarray with the appearance  
of political consultant James Carville, a close friend of the 
president's and one of his staunchest defenders, and also a 
political adviser to Barak during his recent successful electoral 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Carville motioned Stanley Greenberg, another veteran Democratic  
consultant who also worked for Barak, to come forward as did Mary 
Matalin, Carville's wife who also is a prominent Republican 
political consultant. Clinton grabbed Matalin and mugged for the 
television cameras. ``Here I am with Mary Matalin,'' he quipped, 
aware of her strong Republican ties. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a moment of frivolity in what had become a long,  
strenuous receiving line. 
</P>
<P>
	The guest list had a large contingent of New Yorkers, reflecting  
the large Jewish population in New York City, but not totally 
unrelated to the fact that Mrs. Clinton is well on her way to 
seeking a Senate seat from the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The congressional guests from New York ranged from Republican  
Rep. Benjamin Gilman to Democratic Rep. Nita Lowey, who gave up her 
plans to run for the Senate in 2000, deferring to the first lady. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 23:49:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cone Wanted Solitude at Perfect Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- David Cone just wanted to be alone. He walked  
off the mound and straight to the clubhouse after each inning. 
</P>
<P>
	No high-fives, no pep talks, no pats on his back.  
</P>
<P>
	After all, perfection is nothing to be trifled with.  
</P>
<P>
	``The only time I talked to David today, was before the game  
when we went over the hitters,'' catcher Joe Girardi said. ``We 
talked about the pitch selection and I didn't say another word the 
rest of the day. Nobody was brave enough to joke with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cone stayed away from his teammates for the first two outs of  
each inning, every time changing his T-shirt that was soaked with 
sweat because of the near 100-degree temperature. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre found Cone in his clubhouse office  
after the sixth inning. Neither had much to say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We walked past each other,'' Torre said. ``I just told him he  
could use my office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the pair met for the next three innings, under the exact  
same circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every inning after that, I made a point of doing it again,''  
Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	When Cone was on the bench just before retaking the mound each  
inning, his teammates completely ignored him, in keeping with 
baseball superstitions. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of them had been through this when David Wells pitched his  
perfect game last season for the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been spoiled by a couple perfect games, and I think that  
helped the mood,'' Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Outfielder and designated hitter Chili Davis was the only one  
who tried to lighten things up. 
</P>
<P>
	He was catching Cone during warmups in the eighth inning and  
told Cone to throw the ball faster. 
</P>
<P>
	`''You can throw the ball as hard as you want. I caught in the  
minors,''' Davis told Cone. ``Even something like that, which 
wasn't very funny, broke the ice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After completing the perfect game and being mobbed by his  
teammates, Cone eventually found himself back at his hideout in 
Torre's office, where he got a congratulatory call from Wells. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankee second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who saved the no-hitter  
with a backhanded grab in the eighth inning, enjoyed Cone's 
perfection more than Wells'. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today was more exciting for me,'' Knoblauch said. ``The guy is  
the ultimate teammate and for him to be able to pull this off was 
amazing. Equally amazing was the fact that this happened on Yogi 
Berra Day and we actually had Don Larsen here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 23:49:51 </DATE_TIME>
