<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 22:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Reacts to JFK Disappearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The presumed death of John F. Kennedy Jr. grabbed  
international headlines for a second day today as newspapers 
recounted his life in the public eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers in Britain ran lengthy obituaries and accounts of the  
string of tragedies that have befallen America's most famous 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sun, the largest selling daily in Britain, led Page One with  
the headline ``Rest in peace'' and a photo of Kennedy as a toddler 
with his father in the White House's Oval Office. 
</P>
<P>
	``Grief and disbelief as U.S. mourns strange death of favorite  
son,'' said the front-page headline in The Independent. 
</P>
<P>
	Some papers played up Kennedy's relative lack of flight  
experience and his tendency to take chances. ``Last fatal risk of a 
daredevil,'' said the headline in The Express. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy was traveling with his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy,  
and sister-in-law, Lauren Bessette, to a family wedding when their 
plane disappeared over the ocean on its way to Martha's Vineyard, 
Mass. Searchers said it was unlikely they would be found alive. 
</P>
<P>
	In Ireland, the home of Kennedy's ancestors, state TV and radio  
channel RTE sent its Washington correspondent to Massachusetts to 
cover what it described as a tragedy for ``the Irish-American 
political dynasty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All of Japan's major daily newspapers ran items today on the  
search, most accompanied by photos, including the famous image of 
the boy Kennedy saluting at his father's funeral. 
</P>
<P>
	The South China Morning Post in Hong Kong ran the Kennedy story  
under the banner headline ``U.S. prays for Kennedy miracle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy himself was not well known in all parts of the world,  
but most know the fabled Kennedy name. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very sad how despite all the fame and riches, that one  
family can be followed by so much bad luck,'' said Giesela Braun, a 
resident of Frankfurt, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Eileen Firman, 49, a London nurse, said she was not nearly as  
affected by the loss of Kennedy as she was by the 1997 death of 
Princess Diana in a Paris car crash. ``Mostly because I didn't know 
him as well,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Israel, Kennedy's disappearance was the top story on all  
radio and television reports and headlined most of Sunday's daily 
newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel's Channel 2 TV station interviewed a former schoolmate of  
Kennedy when he was at private school in New York in the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	``He insisted on being an ordinary kid. Every day, we took the  
bus from Fifth Avenue to the West Side and he insisted on taking 
the bus with us,'' said Daniel Diker. ``He was a nice guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pope John Paul II, vacationing in the Italian Alps, said he was  
praying for the whole Kennedy clan. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's acting prime minister, Tim Fischer, sent a message  
of sympathy to the Kennedy family. 
</P>
<P>
	Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi also expressed his ``sorrow for  
the loss of John Kennedy Jr.'' He went on to castigate U.S. 
authorities for their failure so far to locate the lost plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy's disappearance was the main story on the front page of  
most major Mexican newspapers. La Cronica carried photos of Kennedy 
with his mother and father and a chronology of other tragedies to 
hit the family. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
