<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conable Sums Up 20 years in House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDER, N.Y. (AP) -- Even as a rookie on the powerful Ways and  
Means Committee in 1967, Barber B. Conable Jr. knew raising a 
million dollars was easier than falling out of bed. 
</P>
<P>
	When a lobbyist came dangling a fat check from a shoe  
manufacturer, Conable made an on-the-spot pledge and shed forever 
his discomfort over donations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `Well, thank you very much, that's a very kind offer,  
but there's a problem: I've decided I'm going to accept no more 
than $50 from anybody,''' he recalls with relish. 
</P>
<P>
	The lobbyist slammed the door on the way out. Conable stuck with  
the pledge for the remaining 18 of 20 years spent in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``I gave rise to a canard that I could be bought cheaper than  
anybody else!'' he exclaims, his deep-barreled laugh echoing 
through his yellow, Palladian-style converted farmhouse in western 
New York's dairy country. 
</P>
<P>
	Observing the bulging campaign war chests of modern campaigns,  
Conable says with a sigh of resignation that overhauling campaign 
finance rules will always be uphill work. ``Policy is made by 
incumbents, incumbents want to stay there and they're the ones who 
get the big money,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Not one to wallow in the past, Conable nonetheless delights in  
summoning up his days in public life -- from casting his lot with 
Gerald Ford in their ascent through Republican Party ranks through 
a long friendship with George Bush that soured over Conable's rocky 
stewardship of the World Bank from 1986 to 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Conable almost doubled the bank's capital budget and  
sharpened its focus on combating poverty and bolstering primary 
education, President Bush ``thought I should be supporting an 
American agenda,'' he says, ``I thought I was there to help the 
poor people. So I got the reputation of not being a team player, 
and that was the one thing George wouldn't stand for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conable always had his own standards to meet. He was that rarest  
of political breeds: a conservative with a socially libertarian 
streak, a deep thinker with a pragmatic flair. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislating was more important to him than partisanship, so it  
was no surprise when both parties judged him the ``most respected'' 
member of the House his final two years in office. ``There never 
has been a better congressman,'' columnist George Will wrote of 
Conable's departure in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	And yet Conable, who rose to become his party's standard bearer  
on taxes, trade and Social Security, knows he'd get little respect 
in today's Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, many members of my party would consider me a loathsome  
liberal,'' he says with equal parts distaste and disbelief. ``They 
would not accept me as a leader in the current Congress because I'm 
too independent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A tall, hearty man with a stentorian voice, erudite yet  
plain-spoken, Conable is happily getting on with his semiprivate 
life. At 76, he has a legacy as a woodlander to work on. 
</P>
<P>
	He's converted his 250-acre backyard from marginal farmland into  
an arboretum dense with 160 tree varieties he collected on world 
travels. Coyote and deer find shelter here. Beavers have 
commandeered a pond. 
</P>
<P>
	Although slowed by heart and knee-replacement surgery, Conable  
says he stays lively enough so ``I won't completely fray at the 
collar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is more selective than before -- serving on the Smithsonian  
Institution board beats joining an ex-Members of Congress club -- 
but still hungers for challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	As host of a weekly public-television talk show called  
``Speaking of Rochester,'' he can revel in familiar terrain: local 
history, anthropology and politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can put things in perspective in a way few people can,''  
says WXXI-TV's president, Norm Silverstein. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone appreciated Conable's perspective. His last  
election foe, Democrat Bill Benet in 1982, thinks he did lasting 
harm to the economy -- and bore partial responsibility for huge 
federal deficits -- by shepherding President Reagan's 25 percent 
income tax cut through Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Conable carried the day for the Reagan tax cuts and the Reagan  
spending cuts and for the buildup of the military budget,'' he 
says. ``...Look at what has happened in this country in terms of 
the shift of wealth away from middle-class people and the fact that 
people are having to work two and three jobs to make ends meet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conable ``was a very decent gentleman, and he did think very  
deeply about the issues,'' Benet adds. ``I just think he was 
wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conable spent his career in the minority, negotiating skillfully  
behind the scenes for scraps from a Democratic Congress, which 
invited criticism that he wasn't as tough as he was fair. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's probably justified,'' he says, a wry, lopsided smile  
pleating his left cheek. ``I was not way out there voting for the 
most extreme, egregious, ridiculous position in the world. 
Compromise is the way things get done in Congress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were bitter disappointments, none greater than the  
betrayal of Watergate after years of loyally backing President 
Nixon's policies. Conable later refused to answer Nixon's letters 
or attend his funeral. 
</P>
<P>
	He counts among the high points his helping force through the  
revenue sharing law in 1972, which made the federal government 
share more money with state and local governments, and the Trade 
Reform Act of 1974, which cleared the way for U.S. negotiations on 
lowering tariff barriers. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps his enduring triumph was winning 10 straight elections  
on a virtual shoestring. The most he ever spent was $76,000 in a 
tight, post-Watergate race. 
</P>
<P>
	If he were still in Congress, where the limit on individual  
contributions is $1,000 in each election, Conable's $50 barrier 
would likely be breached. 
</P>
<P>
	Deadpans Harry Nicholas, his longtime administrative assistant,  
``He might make it $100 now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
