<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shriver Book Discusses Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As the nation's most famously tragedy-torn  
family grapples with the presumed death of John Kennedy Jr., a 
fast-selling book by Maria Shriver is advising thousands of 
children on coping with death. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``What's Heaven?,'' published in March, Ms. Shriver drew on  
her own experience handling the death of one uncle, President 
Kennedy, when she was 8, and the death of another, Robert F. 
Kennedy, at 12. The NBC correspondent wrote the book after her own 
children began asking about the 1995 death of family matriarch Rose 
Fitzgerald Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, a fictional conversation between a girl named Kate and  
her mother, offers a nondenominational view of heaven in which 
angels escort the soul to the clouds and the body remains behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to say goodbye to someone you love, but it's also  
important to know that the sadness won't last forever,'' Kate says. 
</P>
<P>
	The book joined a John Grisham thriller on The New York Times'  
best-seller list, becoming the first children's book to crack the 
top 10 since Dr. Seuss in the 1960s. It was on the best-seller list 
for seven weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you associate Maria Shriver's name with it, you don't  
know what's going to happen,'' said Sandra Speidel, a Petaluma, 
Calif., artist who illustrated the book. 
</P>
<P>
	The book was intended as an adult gift book, Ms. Speidel said,  
but has become best known as a children's title. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea was not to make it too literal but to convey that  
sense of what a child might imagine heaven to look like or what we 
imagine it to look like,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Shriver, 43, said in a Good Housekeeping magazine interview  
published in March that she was trying to answer questions that 
might be asked by her four children: Katherine, 9; Christina, 7; 
Patrick, 5; and Christopher, 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was growing up, there was a lot of loss around,'' she  
said. ``I also grew up at a time when you didn't talk about it. I'd 
think, I know somebody just died, but nobody's talking about it, so 
I better not talk about it either. Even though I knew the whole 
world was talking about it. ... This was a motivation for me to 
write the book.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book includes hints of how Ms. Shriver has dealt with her  
family's repeated brushes with tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Kate's mother tells her: ``No one who goes to heaven is  
forgotten. Their friends and family always remember them. So, in a 
way, they live in all of us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
