<DOCNO> APW19990718.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 23:20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coast Guard Says Kennedy Likely Dead  
</P>
<P>
	AQUINNAH, Mass. (AP) -- After two days of searching, authorities  
conceded late Sunday that John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and her 
sister likely were dead. ``We are going to shift, and I say shift 
very purposefully, from our focus on search and rescue to search 
and recovery,'' Coast Guard Rear Adm. Richard M. Larrabee, the head 
of the search operation, said at a news conference. Larrabee noted 
that it would be difficult for a person to survive more than 18 
hours in the area's 68-degree waters. He also said the search for 
Kennedy's missing plane, which has covered almost 9,000 square 
miles, on Sunday produced no major finds but authorities were 
focusing on ``a couple of targets.'' 

</P>
<P>
	World Reacts to JFK Disappearance  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The presumed death of John F. Kennedy Jr. grabbed  
international headlines for a second day Monday as newspapers 
recounted his life in the public eye. Newspapers in Britain ran 
lengthy obituaries and accounts of the string of tragedies that 
have befallen America's most famous family. In Ireland state TV and 
radio channel RTE sent its Washington correspondent to 
Massachusetts to cover what it described as a tragedy for ``the 
Irish-American political dynasty.'' All of Japan's major daily 
newspapers ran items Monday on the search, most accompanied by 
photos, including the famous image of the boy Kennedy saluting at 
his father's funeral. The South China Morning Post in Hong Kong ran 
the Kennedy story under the banner headline ``U.S. prays for 
Kennedy miracle.'' 

</P>
<P>
	UN Seeks More Protection for Serbs  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Revenge attacks on Kosovo's  
remaining Serbs have prompted a U.N. representative to ask for more 
international help to protect civilians. NATO has struggled to 
prevent returning ethnic Albanian refugees from seeking revenge 
against Kosovo's Serbian minority since Serbian forces pulled out 
of the province and alliance troops began moving in last month 
under a peace accord. U.N. representative Bernard Kouchner's 
comments after talks Sunday with Kosovo Serb politician Momcilo 
Trajkovic and Orthodox Bishop Artemije appeared to signal concern 
about the Serbs' fate. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak, Clinton Promote Peace Agenda  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Sunday night Israeli  
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has made it ``very clear that Israel will 
keep its commitments'' for peace in the Middle East and ``America 
will do its part.'' Clinton and Barak exchanged toasts at a dinner 
attended by 400 guests including Leah Rabin, widow of the late 
Israeli prime minister. Earlier, Barak called the United States 
``maybe the best ally we have'' and pledged to get a peace accord 
with the Arabs in 15 months. 

</P>
<P>
	Dissidents Say They Killed 4 Iraqis  
</P>
<P>
	DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- An Iraqi opposition group claimed Sunday  
that its guerrillas in southern Iraq killed four security officials 
and wounded two others in an attack on a checkpoint. The Islamic 
Action Organization, or IAO, a Shiite Muslim group based in Syria, 
said the attack was carried out Saturday after locals complained 
about ``despicable behavior'' by the security officials at the 
checkpoint. The claim could not be independently verified. The 
Iraqi government does not respond to reports by opposition groups. 

</P>
<P>
	China May Use Force Against Taiwan  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- President Jiang Zemin told President Clinton  
Sunday that China has not ruled out using force against Taiwan if 
the island tries to split from the mainland, according to the 
official Xinhua News Agency. The report was the highest-level 
threat yet in an eight-day-old Chinese war of words against the 
island, which Beijing regards as a renegade province. Jiang made 
the comment in a telephone call to Clinton, Xinhua said. China and 
Taiwan have been ruled separately since a civil war 50 years ago. 
Both say they are part of the same country. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Midday Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Monday morning. The Nikkei  
rose 178.40 points to finish the morning session at 18,426.70. 

</P>
<P>
	Rangers 5, Giants 4  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Mike Morgan won for the fourth time in  
five decisions, becoming Texas' first 10-game winner of the season 
as the Rangers beat the San Francisco Giants 5-4 Sunday night. 
Morgan allowed three runs and seven hits in 6 1-3 innings, struck 
out two and walked one. John Wetteland pitched the ninth for his 
27th save in 34 opportunities. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets 8, Orioles 6  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Rickey Henderson hit a leadoff homer and former  
Orioles closer Armando Benitez sealed Masato Yoshii's first win in 
a month as the New York Mets ended Baltimore's five-game winning 
streak, 8-6 Sunday night. New York led 8-1 but let Baltimore close 
within two runs before bringing in Benitez, who entered in the 
ninth to a chorus of boos from those left in the crowd of 47,480. 

</P>
