<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coast Guard Searches for JFK Jr. Plane  
</P>
<P>
	AQUINNAH, Mass. (AP) -- Coast Guard cutters using bright lights  
and a sonar-equipped submersible continued the search early today 
for John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and her sister. A daylong search 
yesterday -- after Kennedy's plane was reported missing off the 
coast of Martha's Vineyard -- yielded plane fragments, a 
prescription bottle belonging to his wife and a piece of baggage 
belonging to his sister-in-law, but no signs of life. A visual 
aerial search suspended late yesterday due to darkness and hazy 
conditions was to resume at first light today with additional 
boats, planes and helicopters. 

</P>
<P>
	Wedding Postponed, Kennedys Pray  
</P>
<P>
	HYANNIS PORT, Mass. (AP) -- The wedding of Rory Kennedy, daughter  
of late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy, was postponed indefinitely 
yesterday as word spread that John Kennedy Jr., his wife, Carolyn 
Bessette Kennedy and her sister, Lauren Bessette were reported 
missing aboard a plane en route to the celebration. The 
bride-to-be's life has been marked by a string of tragedies. Her 
father, the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy, was assassinated before 
she was born and she was the one who cradled her dying brother, 
Michael, after a skiing accident in 1997. Some 275 guests were 
expected for the private 6 p.m. wedding ceremony. 

</P>
<P>
	War Prosecutor Advises Rehabilitation  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Local courts in the former  
Yugoslavia must be rehabilitated so that they eventually can help 
handle some of the growing caseload, the chief prosecutor for the 
international war crimes tribunal said yesterday. Louise Arbour is 
on her last tour of the region before leaving her post in The 
Hague, Netherlands. ``I think that it's critical that we 
participate and assist in full rehabilitation of domestic courts so 
that they can undertake a significant share of prosecuting war 
criminals,'' she said. 

</P>
<P>
	Pinochet Denies Human Rights Abuses  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Former Chilean dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet has  
denied direct involvement in human rights abuses, The Sunday 
Telegraph reported. ``I didn't have time to control what others 
were doing,'' the newspaper quoted Pinochet as saying. Instead, 
Pinochet said he concentrated on turning the country away from the 
Marxist path charted by democratically elected President Salvador 
Allende, whom he helped overthrow in a 1973 coup. Spain is seeking 
to extradite Pinochet, who was arrested Oct. 16 in London on 
charges he ordered the torture of opponents during his 17-year 
rule. 

</P>
<P>
	Dole Pushes Farm Relief Package  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Former Cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole  
yesterday demanded a farm disaster relief package larger than the 
$6 billion approved by Congress last year. Opening her latest 
campaign swing, Mrs. Dole became the latest candidate to focus on a 
struggling farm economy that's important in Iowa, where precinct 
caucuses launch the presidential nominating season. While most 
sectors of the economy have been humming along well and the stock 
market has soared, farmers have been struggling with historically 
low commodity prices. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Rep. Forbes Joining Democrats  
</P>
<P>
	QUOGUE, N.Y. (AP) -- Republican lawmaker Michael Forbes switched  
allegiance to the Democrats yesterday, the first such defection 
since the GOP took control of Congress five years ago. He drew 
praise from President Clinton for having the ``courage to change'' 
and scorn from the GOP for placing ``ego ahead of principle.'' 
Forbes, who represents the eastern tip of New York's Long Island, 
told reporters at his home that the Republican Party ``has become 
an angry, narrow-minded, intolerant and uncaring majority, 
incapable of governing at all, much less from the center, and 
tone-deaf to the concerns of a vast majority of Americans.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Vargas Stops Marquez  
</P>
<P>
	STATELINE, Nev. (AP) -- Fernando Vargas, forced into the longest  
fight of his pro career, stopped Raul Marquez midway through the 
11th round to retain his IBF junior middleweight title last night. 
Vargas kept his record perfect, winning his 17th straight fight, 
but had to go past the seventh round for the first time in his 
career. Referee Joe Cortez stopped the fight 2:00 into the 11th 
round as Vargas pounded Marquez along the ropes. Vargas, 21, a 1996 
U.S. Olympian from Oxnard, Calif., opened cuts around both of 
Marquez's eyes in making his second successful defense of the 
154-pound title he captured last December. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras and O'Brien Stop Sweep  
</P>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Pete Sampras and Alex O'Brien rescued  
their despondent Davis Cup teammates yesterday, stopping an 
Australian sweep and giving the United States hope going into the 
final singles matches. Sampras and O'Brien persevered through 
nearly 3 1/2 hours to stave off elimination in the quarterfinals with 
a 6-4, 6-3, 3-6, 4-6, 6-3 victory. Now it's up to Todd Martin in a 
match tomorrow against Patrick Rafter, and Jim Courier in the 
second match against Lleyton Hewitt, to see if they can pull off a 
comeback from 0-2 in the best-of-5 duel. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
