<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 23:40:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Working on Y2K Repairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Come New Year's Eve, the Concorde will be  
turned into a time machine, its passengers marking the start of the 
new century in Paris before streaking back across the time zones 
and celebrating midnight again in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Just across the English Channel in London, the planes of Virgin  
Atlantic Airways will be anything but supersonic. Instead, they'll 
be parked on the ramp, grounded as 1999 turns to 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers blistering across the ocean at 1,400 mph, a $10,000  
ticket in hand. Jumbo jets sitting idle and empty on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Those will be the two extremes in the airline industry as the  
Y2K witching hour arrives, bringing with it uncertainty about how 
computers will behave. Such uncertainty is especially troublesome 
in the aviation business, where everything from radar to aircraft 
fueling orders are computerized. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration insists it has fixed its  
``mission-critical'' equipment so it can handle the rollover. Some 
older computers viewed dates in a two-digit format -- ``99'' for 
1999 -- generating concern they will malfunction as the new century 
begins. Unrepaired computers may construe the new ``00'' as 1900 
instead of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's major airlines say they are 95 percent done with  
their own repairs and will be finished by September. 
</P>
<P>
	To date, only Virgin Atlantic, LOT Polish Airlines, Vietnam  
Airlines and a small British regional carrier have said they will 
not fly on New Year's Eve. Virgin says it's not because of Y2K 
concerns, but so employees can celebrate a unique milestone with 
their families. 
</P>
<P>
	Qantas, the airline of Australia, has taken a slightly different  
tack. It has ordered its executives not to fly. Airline chief James 
Strong said in April he wanted his decision makers on the ground 
and in the board room that night, ready to deal with any problems 
that might crop up. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be quite the opposite in China. There, the Communist  
government has ordered its airline executives to fly, exhibiting 
confidence that the country has addressed its computer problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the world's airlines say that, as of now, they will  
be flying as usual for the lull between Christmas and New Year's, 
which means at about 75 percent of their normal capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	British Airways, Virgin Atlantic's bitter rival, says it may  
even be busier than usual thanks to a huge millennium bash in 
London and the city's closeness to Greenwich, England, where 
Greenwich Mean Time is marked. 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry has been preparing for it for some time,'' said  
Mary Pat Sullivan, publisher of Leisure Travel News, a weekly trade 
publication. ``Consumer interest was high early, but things are 
starting to tail off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She expects deals on airplane tickets in the near future. One  
special flight is nearly sold out, though. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Pevsner, a tour operator who has arranged record-breaking  
flights around the world on the Concorde, has chartered one of Air 
France's supersonic jets for perhaps the ultimate New Year's 
celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	Travelers will party in the hours leading up to midnight at an  
airport hotel and move to the aircraft close to the stroke of 
midnight. A half hour into the new century, their jet will take 
off. 
</P>
<P>
	For the next 3 1/2 hours, they will indulge in a variety of  
champagne and other first-class fare while the in-cabin speedometer 
ticks steadily higher, eventually hitting a top speed of 1,400 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	At a cruise altitude of nearly 60,000 feet -- over 11 miles high,  
or about double the height of standard jetliners -- they will be 
able to see the curvature of the Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	After they descend for a landing in New York about 10 p.m. back  
on Dec. 31, private helicopters will whisk them over the traffic 
below and on to Times Square, for their second countdown of the 
evening. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be the only people seeing in the New Year in  
both Europe and the United States,'' Pevsner said of he and the 
other 99 travelers on his trip. ``They see it as a totally unique 
way to see in the millennium.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
