<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers Prayers for Kennedys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying the Kennedys ``have suffered much and  
given more'' as a family, a grim-faced President Clinton offered 
the prayers of a nation on Sunday as authorities scanned the ocean 
in hopes of finding the son of the one president Clinton personally 
idolized. 
</P>
<P>
	Arriving at the White House from Camp David, Md., Clinton  
thanked the Coast Guard and other searchers who are trolling the 
coast off Martha's Vineyard, where wreckage from a private plane 
carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy and 
sister-in-law Lauren Bessette began washing ashore on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this difficult moment, we hope the families of these three  
fine young people will feel the strength of God, the love of their 
friends and the prayers of their fellow citizens,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke several hours before Coast Guard officials announced  
Sunday evening that the military focus was shifting from a search 
and rescue operation to a search and wreckage recovery operation. 
</P>
<P>
	His words rang with personal loss. The Clintons have spent time  
with the Kennedys during vacations on Martha's Vineyard, sharing 
boating excursions and dinners at a compound once owned by 
Kennedy's late mother, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis. 
</P>
<P>
	``For more than 40 years now, the Kennedy family has inspired  
Americans to public service, strengthened our faith in the future 
and moved our nation forward,'' Clinton said. ``Through it all, 
they have suffered much and given more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Kennedy and his wife, who were married almost three  
years ago, ``have captured our imagination and won our affection'' 
in recent years. He said he would always be grateful ``for their 
kindnesses to Hillary and Chelsea and me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton stepped off his helicopter with his wife and daughter.  
They locked hands and walked in unison across the lawn, Mrs. 
Clinton sandwiched in the middle. When he finished speaking, 
Clinton swallowed hard and disappeared into the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	The president spoke just a few feet away from the Rose Garden  
where, as a teen-ager, he met President Kennedy on July 24, 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	Back then, Clinton was one among several attending Boys Nation.  
When he graduated high school, young Clinton scribbled his name 
below a photograph of himself and Kennedy in the yearbooks of his 
friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is unabashed in his admiration of Kennedy, and weaves  
Kennedy influences into his policies and actions in a variety of 
ways. For example, when Clinton journeyed to Africa last year, he 
made Ghana his first stop because it was the first nation where 
Kennedy's Peace Corps began operating. 
</P>
<P>
	He once said Kennedy's emphasis on public service ``taught me to  
believe in America. ... He made it seem fun and noble and good. The 
best we can do is to keep the torch burning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to David Maraniss' 1995 biography, ``First in His  
Class,'' Clinton wrote a letter to his mother while studying at 
Georgetown, telling her that a friend who had worked for Kennedy, 
Tommy Caplan, was preparing to spend time with an especially 
precocious toddler. 
</P>
<P>
	``John Kennedy Jr. is supposed to visit him at Georgetown  
sometime this year,'' Clinton wrote. ``He is only three years old, 
but this boy says he is a really smart boy and just like his 
daddy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an adult, the younger Kennedy found his way back to the White  
House -- on Clinton's invitation. 
</P>
<P>
	When Clinton announced the first woman to command a U.S. space  
shuttle mission, Kennedy was there, in the audience. He brought 
along his wife in February 1998, when Clinton played host to a 
state dinner for British Prime Minister Tony Blair. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy bowed as he greeted Hillary Rodham Clinton and Cherie  
Blair, while Bessette removed her long evening gloves before 
shaking Clinton's hand. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, Vice President Al Gore canceled a Sunday brunch  
that was to raise funds for his presidential campaign. He attended 
Mass at the Sacred Heart Church, and told reporters afterward that 
his prayers were with the Kennedy family. 
</P>
<P>
	``Above all, we are reminded of the sacrifices of the Kennedy  
family, and how precious and fragile life is,'' Gore said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
