<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Midday Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Monday morning, bolstered by  
Friday's record closing-high on Wall Street and expectations the 
Japanese government may consider a supplementary budget. The U.S. 
dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 178.40 points,  
or 0.98 percent, to finish the morning session at 18,426.70. On 
Friday, the average closed down 183.56 points, or 1.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.55 yen at late morning, down 0.37 yen from  
late Friday in Tokyo and also below its late Friday New York level 
of 120.95 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices started higher after the Dow Jones  
industrial average rose 23.43 points to a record 11,209.84 Friday. 
The Standard and Poor's 500 stock index and high-tech heavy Nasdaq 
Composite Index also closed at record highs. 
</P>
<P>
	A report in Monday's Nihon Keizai financial newspaper quoting  
Economic Planning Agency Director-General Taichi Sakaiya as saying 
Japan may need a supplementary budget of about 5 trillion yen (dlrs 
41 billion) for the current fiscal year was also providing support, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, traders weren't expecting any sharp advances in the  
market ahead of a national holiday in Japan on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult to expect the market to go sharply higher in  
the afternoon ahead of the holiday,'' said Hidenori Karaki, general 
manager at Tokyo-Mitsubishi Personal Securities, 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 7.70 points, or 0.51 percent, to 1,514.72. The 
TOPIX closed down 4.71 points, or 0.31 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar remained lower as demand for the  
yen was rising amid the Tokyo stock market's gains, traders said. 
The euro's weakness against the yen also indirectly weighed on the 
greenback, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the dollar's retreat against the Japanese currency  
would be limited on continued fears over possible intervention by 
the Bank of Japan to prevent the yen from rising. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has intervened to buy the greenback several  
times in recent weeks to keep the yen from rising. A higher yen 
make Japanese exports more expensive abroad and thus less 
competitive, cutting into earnings of export-oriented Japanese 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 121.92 yen, down  
from 123.34 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.7800 percent from Friday's finish of 1.7550 percent, 
driving its price down to 100.17 yen from 100.38 yen. 
</P>
<P>
 *(ep-dj-km) 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
