<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 23:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ricky Martin Concert Sells Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta fans went loco for tickets to Latin  
sensation Ricky Martin's upcoming concert. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oct. 24 show sold out in 30 minutes. Even at $97 apiece, the  
best of the 15,000 seats at the new Philips Arena, which hasn't 
even opened yet, were the first to go when they went on sale 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a hot show. It's the best sales we could have ever  
expected,'' said concert promoter Amy Helbert of Concert Southern 
Promotions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta concert is the only one scheduled in the Southeast,  
outside Florida, on a 15-city tour this fall, Ms. Helbert said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ricky Martin,'' the first English-language CD from the  
27-year-old singer, had the best-ever album debut by a Hispanic 
artist on the mainstream Billboard charts. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Rico native Rick Nieves snapped up two tickets for his  
teen-age daughters. He said he watched Martin's career take off 
during the early 1980s in Puerto Rico as the singer climbed to 
heartthrob status with the group Menudo. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was popular then, but now he's exploded with a new sound.  
The Latino influence is catching on,'' Nieves said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 10:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vt. Newsletter Prints All the News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	READING, Vt. (AP) -- Did you know that Anita Pascaret has been  
having back problems? Or that Marjorie Matthews ``has a house full 
of company''? Or that Mr. Wastrom has been ``finishing the back 
wall of the church and then will be doing the schoolhouse''? Or 
that the annual picnic of the Old Stone Church had ``plenty of food 
for all''? 
</P>
<P>
	You would know that and much, much more if you were a faithful  
reader of Eva Gasper's weekly column in the Vermont Standard. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gasper is 96, and for the past 20 years she has been  
sending the Standard all the news from the town of Reading, in 
southeastern Vermont. 
</P>
<P>
	And that means all the news.  
</P>
<P>
	The Vermont Standard, published 20 miles away in Woodstock, has  
a circulation of 4,500 and is one of several weekly newspapers in 
the state that still place a premium on the most local of news -- 
that generated by someone who knows the community and its people. 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly Mrs. Gasper does. She has lived in Reading since 1909.  
</P>
<P>
	She says Reading, with its population of around 700, is a ``very  
small place so it doesn't have much news.'' But you would never 
know it from reading her column. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past month readers have learned:  
</P>
<P>
	``Anita Pascaret has been in the hospital, suffering with her  
back. She is home now, but can't get out. I was sorry to hear this. 
She is a lovely lady, and sings in our choir.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The sixth grade graduation took place last weekend. They went  
to Wells, Maine, on a whale watch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Wastrom is here finishing the back wall of the church, and  
then will be doing the schoolhouse. I don't know how much he can 
get done, hopefully two walls. He is a busy man, and has all the 
work he can get done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gasper says some weeks there is too little news to fill a  
column, ``But I have to write a column on something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So tucked throughout are references to residents' birthdays and  
anniversaries and personal notes, such as, ``Bought myself a fan 
and love it'' and, ``Everyone is hoping for rain. It surely is 
needed badly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For many years when Mrs. Gasper would run out of news, she would  
wind up her column with memories of growing up in Reading at the 
beginning of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	``I carried that for a while, but even that ran out.''  
</P>
<P>
	So occasionally she ventures into the wider world with  
observations such as: ``Wow, so many are running for president of 
the United States... I like the vice president... 
</P>
<P>
	``There are things we all must look for getting the right one to  
run the country, to keep the economy up there, work for all, 
education for all, keep Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid. 
One cannot look at party alone, but for the one who can give these 
things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A column following Memorial Day combined personal memories and  
commentary as she wrote about the two World Wars and the troubles 
in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	When World War I broke out ``I was a teen-ager then and recall  
so well how grand they all looked in uniform... World War II came 
soon after... It took away all the serenity I remember so well. Now 
another war is on. How many of our boys are going to be taken, 
before peace will be had? What will happen to so many out of homes 
and necessities of life?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not all of the local columns in the Vermont weeklies are as full  
of personal news and insights as is Mrs. Gasper's. But all provide 
an intimate look into small-town life, telling readers things that 
otherwise might not get around. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a holdover from the past but it has come to be part of  
the paper that sets us apart from other publications,'' says Kevin 
Forrest, 47, the editor of the Standard. ``It makes us truly local. 
It gives us the neighborhood feeling. Plus it is just good 
down-home entertainment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gasper, a small woman with a spirit that makes her seem  
twice her size and half her age, starts work on her column each 
Saturday, sitting in her comfortable chair in the living room, 
telephone in hand, pad and pen at the ready as she works her way 
through a list of people she calls weekly in her hunt for news. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't get out much,'' she says. ``I don't drive and I don't  
get to see very much so I have to find out what I can from the 
telephone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She takes notes of her conversations and at the end of the day  
pulls out a typewriter and writes about half of her column. She 
spends most of Sunday at church and Bible study -- ``It's a 
tremendously busy day'' -- but when she gets home finishes the 
column, often dropping in nuggets picked up from church. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gasper isn't in it for the money. There is no regular pay  
for the column. ``We get a bonus at Christmas time that I use to 
buy gifts and we get the paper free and we get to advertise free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She says she loves the task. ``I don't feel any different at 96  
than I did at 50. This keeps me going. I tell Kevin I ought to quit 
and he should get someone younger, but he keeps telling me that 
people like what I write.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like the local drama. A few weeks ago the following was  
revealed: 
</P>
<P>
	``On Friday night of this week we went shopping and out for  
pizza. It didn't look so good so Mrs. Pugh tried a little piece of 
it, and afterward was taken with terrible chills, vomiting, cold 
sweats, etc. She thought she was dying. She was too sick to go to 
the hospital. She thinks it could have been the cheese. She is 
feeling some better today, but a ways to go before she can do 
much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The July 1 edition of the Standard brought this update:  
</P>
<P>
	``Mrs. Pugh went to see the doctor, and found she has a bladder  
infection. It wasn't the pizza after all.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
