<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Search for JFK Jr. Draws Former Foes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AQUINNAH, Mass. (AP) -- The search for John F. Kennedy Jr. drew  
many helping hands, even those of American Indians who fiercely 
battled his mother over rights to the land he was flying toward 
when his plane vanished. 
</P>
<P>
	As the search stretched into a second day on Sunday, the help  
included three rangers from the Wampanoag Tribe, who had fought 
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis over a small plot of land within her 
estate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's our nature to help out,'' said William D. Vanderhoop, a  
Wampanoag who has lived in Aquinnah all his 69 years. ``We don't 
have bows and arrows and tomahawks here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1980s, Mrs. Onassis was locked in a dispute with tribal  
members over a 1.5-acre plot of land completely surrounded by her 
365-acre seaside estate. The plot was considered sacred by tribal 
members, who have lived on the island for centuries. Mrs. Onassis 
wanted to buy the land to ensure her privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides battled for 10 years before settling in 1990. The  
Wampanoags agreed to surrender the site for $100,000 and two acres 
closer to the nearest road. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribal historian June Manning sat on a bench in front of the Gay  
Head lighthouse Sunday afternoon and faced the Onassis home, which 
John Kennedy Jr. and his sister, Caroline, inherited from their 
mother in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``That shows you we don't hold grudges,'' Manning said. ``It  
shows the humanitarianism in us, which defines us as a tribal 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also volunteering in the huge search for Kennedy and his  
passengers, his wife and sister-in-law, were civilian pilots from 
up to 100 miles away and fishermen with depth-finders and years of 
knowledge about the waters around Aquinnah. 
</P>
<P>
	Herbie Hancock, a lobsterman who skippers the Billy H. out of  
Menemsha Harbor, said he and other fishermen were willing to lend 
their nets and depth-finders but had stayed away so they wouldn't 
interfere with the search. 
</P>
<P>
	Others agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``They don't need people crisscrossing the area, tossing over  
sandwich wrappers. It's just better to let them to do their job,'' 
said a tugboat skipper who would not give his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Official searchers acknowledged that doing their duty this time  
had special poignancy because the object of their search was so 
celebrated and his family so well-known locally. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Col. Don Desfosse, an auxiliary pilot from Hanscom Air Force  
Base in Bedford, Mass., spent Sunday in a small plane patrolling at 
1,500 feet about 20 miles southwest of Aquinnah. 
</P>
<P>
	Every time Desfosse and his crew thought they saw something in  
the water, he said, their hearts would race. And then there would 
be nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a shame,'' he said. ``Time to press on and find something  
real.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
