<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Thunderstorms and rain flowed across the upper Midwest on  
Sunday, and scattered thunderstorms also developed across wide 
areas of the South. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms and locally heavy rain stretched from central  
North Dakota into northeastern South Dakota, most of southern 
Minnesota and northern Iowa during the middle of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The storms moved rapidly eastward, and by late afternoon radar  
showed the heaviest rain falling across the southern half of 
Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	In the South, scattered thunderstorms developed late in the  
morning near the coast of the Gulf of Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	During the heat of the afternoon, those storms rapidly became  
more numerous and spread inland, stretching over coastal Texas and 
expanding across Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama and Florida, and 
through Georgia into parts of South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Locally heavy rain fell in some southern sections of Texas and  
Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	During the afternoon, widely scattered storms and showers  
developed along the length of the Appalachian chain, from northern 
Alabama and Georgia all the way into northern New England. 
</P>
<P>
	Monsoon weather returned to the Southwest, with showers and a  
few thunderstorms spreading across Arizona, New Mexico and parts of 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Isolated showers also were possible in parts of southern  
California, Nevada and Utah, as well as Washington, Idaho, Wyoming 
and Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures climbed back into the upper 90s along parts of the  
Eastern Seaboard, but cool air in the Northwest produced a record 
low for the date of just 37 degrees at LaGrande, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 31 at Meacham, Ore., to a midday reading of 96 at 
Palm Springs, Calif. The lowest wind chill was 26 at Burns, Ore., 
and the highest midday heat index was 104 at Chesapeake, Va., and 
Wilmington, Del. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
