<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- After starting out the season like Superman, Juan  
Montoya is beginning to look a lot more human. 
</P>
<P>
	The 23-year-old Colombian rookie crashed out of Sunday's Toronto  
Molson Indy, failing to finish for the second straight race. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya, who still leads Dario Franchitti, Sunday's winner, by  
seven points in the season standings, won four times and finished 
in the points (the top 12) in eight of the first nine CART FedEx 
Series races he ran. 
</P>
<P>
	The precocious rookie started eighth and was running solidly in  
the top 10 on Sunday until he was penalized to the rear of the 
lead-lap cars for running over Tony Kanaan's air hose in the pits. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya was battling back, racing Michel Jourdain Jr. for ninth  
place, when the two came together and crashed on lap 60 of the 
95-lap event in the streets of downtown Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	``This weekend was a disaster,'' Montoya said. ``We struggled  
with the car on Friday and Saturday, but the race was looking good. 
After I ran over the hose, I was coming back, but I got stuck 
behind Max (Papis). 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I was trying to pass Jourdain on the inside coming into  
the corner. Once we came out of the corner, I didn't see him on the 
left and we touched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jourdain had a slightly different description.  
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to pass Montoya at the exit of turn three,  
side-by-side. But at the next turn, he didn't allow me to pass, 
squeezing me into the wall. In the process, he touched the front of 
my car and in the rebound, my right rear touched Montoya's left 
rear and we both were unable to continue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jourdain was scored 21st and Montoya 22nd, by far his worst CART  
finish. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SUPERSUB IS BACK: Roberto Moreno bounced back from a non-finish  
at Road America to finish fourth Sunday in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	The 40-year-old Brazilian earned the nickname ``Supersub'' by  
finishing in the points in his first five races filling in for 
PacWest Motorsports Group driver Mark Blundell. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, he came all the way from 17th in the 27-car field to  
match his best PacWest result and make it six points finishes in 
seven starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't have the fastest car today, but we made the most of  
what we had,'' Moreno said. 
</P>
<P>
	Blundell broke his collarbone in a crash during testing in  
Madison, Ill., on May 4. He is scheduled to return to the car on 
Aug. 8 in Detroit. Moreno will remain in the car next week for the 
U.S. 500 at Michigan Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HAT MAN: CART chief Steward Wally Dallenbach, known for his  
cowboy boots and 10-gallon hat, made good on a bet Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallenbach had a standing offer to Christian Fittipaldi since  
the Brazilian driver joined the Champ Car series in 1995 that he 
would give up his trademark brown Stetson hat with the feathered 
band when Fittipaldi got his first win. 
</P>
<P>
	It took Fittipaldi 71 races to get to that first checkered flag,  
but Dallenbach, as promised, handed over the hat during the prerace 
driver's meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Fittipaldi wore it proudly during the postrace press conference  
after finishing third on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HIT MAN: Greg Moore had a terrible day.  
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian driver started 10th and ran among the leaders until  
Michael Andretti ran into the back of his car on lap 12, sending 
Moore spinning. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the race, he collided with Al Unser Jr. as the two  
battled for position. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Moore retired with a reported cooling system failure on  
lap 67, relegating him to 20th place. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like a pinball machine,'' he said. ``I got hit twice.  
The first hit was harder and I think that's what caused the 
mechanical problem that took me out of the race later on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With a non-points finish, Moore fell to seventh in the  
standings, trailing Montoya by 32 points. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SPARK PLUGS: Franchitti is the eighth different winner in 11  
CART races this season. Of his four career victories, three have 
come on temporary road circuits. ... Patrick Racing teammates 
Adrian Fernandez and P.J. Jones gained a total of 17 places between 
them in Sunday's race, with Fernandez starting 23rd and finishing 
sixth and Jones starting 20th and finishing 10th. ... Honda drivers 
have won the last 10 CART races on temporary street circuits, 
dating to April of 1998 in Long Beach. ... Al Unser Jr., who 
finished ninth, made his 265th career start, breaking out of a tie 
with retired Bobby Rahal for the most starts in CART history. He is 
the only active driver to have run in all 14 races in Toronto. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 14:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle Signs Its No. 1 Draft Choice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Mariners on Sunday announced they  
signed high school catcher Ryan Christianson, their first-round 
pick and the 11th overall selection in last month's baseball draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Christianson, 18, from Arlington High School in Riverside,  
Calif., will report to the Mariners' rookie league team in Peoria, 
Ariz. If he plays well there, he could be elevated to Class A 
Everett of the Northwest League in ``a couple of weeks,'' said 
Frank Mattox, the team's director of scouting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our plan is to get him going in Peoria,'' Mattox said at a  
news conference. ``The main thing now is to get him playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Reynolds, Christianson's agent, said his client signed a  
standard minor-league contract with a signing bonus, but neither he 
nor Mattox would reveal its terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``After three years hopefully, he'll be good enough where the  
Mariners want to put him on their 40-man roster,'' Reynolds said. 
</P>
<P>
	Christianson is a 6-foot-2, 210-pounder who is a right-handed  
hitter. He batted .514 (38-for-74) with eight homers and 40 RBIs in 
his senior high school season, helping his team post a 29-2 record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'll be a little bit disappointed if I'm not up here  
in at least four years,'' Christianson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 17:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil 3, Uruguay 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Brazil repeated as South American  
champion, beating Uruguay 3-0 Sunday on a pair of goals by Rivaldo 
and another by Ronaldo to win the America Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that the others were bad, but Brazil right now is  
superior,'' defender Roberto Carlos said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil, which last year lost to France in the World Cup final,  
went ahead in the 21st minute when Flavio Conceicao curled in a 
free kick from the left side and Rivaldo headed it past goalkeeper 
Fabian Carini from the near post. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivaldo scored again six minutes later, taking a cross from Ze  
Roberto, trapping the ball, shaking his defender with a dribble and 
gently chipping the ball over Carini. 
</P>
<P>
	Barely a minute into the second half, Rivaldo spotted Ronaldo on  
a breakaway and sent a perfect pass to the forward, who sent a hard 
shot past Carini to make it 3-0. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an especially happy moment, because it's been a  
difficult year for me,'' said Ronaldo, who was a non-factor when he 
played hurt in the World Cup final, struggled with tendinitis in 
his knees during the Italian League season and broke up with his 
fiance. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronaldo and Rivaldo scored five goals each, tied for the lead in  
the biennial tournament. Brazil, the only four-time World Cup 
champion, outscored opponents 17-2 in winning its sixth South 
American title. Uruguay and Argentina have the most, 14 each. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first phase of our project to prepare for the  
Olympics and the 2002 World Cup,'' Brazil coach Wanderley 
Luxemburgo said. ``We're happy with the win, but our minds are on 
the World Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil plays the United States on July 28 in the FIFA  
Confederations Cup at Guadalajara, Mexico. Ronaldo, a two-time 
world player of the year, is not making the trip for that 
tournament. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
