<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 10:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Still No Signs of JFK Jr.  
</P>
<P>
	AQUINNAH, Mass. (AP) -- A massive aerial search of the sea off  
Martha's Vineyard that resumed today has yet to find any signs of 
John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and her sister. Their plane was 
reported missing off the shores off the resort island early 
yesterday. At a news conference, police Capt. Robert Bird appealed 
to the public to turn over any debris that might be related to the 
crash, noting that holding on to such evidence is a criminal 
offense. Yesterday's search yielded plane fragments, a prescription 
bottle belonging to Kennedy's wife and a piece of baggage belonging 
to his sister-in-law, but no signs of life. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Army Warns Opposition  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav's top general blasted  
increasingly vocal opponents of President Slobodan Milosevic as 
traitors, in remarks published today, amid growing infighting on 
the part of opposition leaders seeking to oust Milosevic. ``Those 
who call for a forceful ouster of the legally elected authorities 
... cannot count on people's support,'' Gen. Dragoljub Ojdanic, the 
army chief of staff, said in remarks published by the 
pro-government daily Politika. The general is one of five top 
officials, including Milosevic, indicted on war crimes charges by 
an international tribunal for alleged atrocities against ethnic 
Albanians in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak's Goal: Peace by Next Year  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said today  
his goal is to reach comprehensive peace with his country's Arab 
neighbors within 15 months and he believes a deal with Syria over 
the Golan Heights would not require the presence of U.S. troops. 
``I believe that within 15 months from now we will know whether we 
have major breakthroughs on the Palestinian, Syrian and Lebanese 
tracks or not,'' Barak told NBC. Barak said any accord on the Golan 
Heights, captured by Israel in its 1967 war with the Arab states, 
could be monitored by a few dozen U.N. observers. 

</P>
<P>
	Iran Says Unrest Funded From Abroad  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Iran's Intelligence Ministry  
said today that some of those arrested during a week of unrest in 
Iran had received money and guidance from abroad. The official 
Islamic Republic News Agency quoted a ministry statement as saying 
that ``funds were deposited in their accounts on a continuous 
basis.'' ``According to confessions and information received by the 
Intelligence Ministry, those who had an active role in the recent 
riots were guided and supported from abroad,'' said IRNA. The 
Intelligence Ministry is controlled by hard-line clerics who were 
the target of the protesters' anger. 

</P>
<P>
	India Secures Most of Kashmir Zone  
</P>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- Thousands of Indian soldiers swept  
across the mountains of northern Kashmir today to verify the 
withdrawal of Pakistani-backed intruders as India's defense 
minister announced that two months of fighting with Muslim 
guerrillas had ended. The army confirmed it has reclaimed three of 
four battle zones in Kashmir and said its soldiers would reoccupy 
Mushkoh Valley, the fourth zone, by first light tomorrow. The two 
months of fighting in Kashmir left as many as 1,250 people dead in 
a conflict that sparked worries of an all-out war between the two 
South Asian neighbors. 

</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde Leads Shrinks  
</P>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Jean Van de Velde lost his  
five-stroke lead but then went to the turn one ahead at the British 
Open today after a strong challenge at Carnoustie from Craig Parry 
and Justin Leonard. Parry wiped out the Frenchman's lead after 
eight holes but Van de Velde then birdied the ninth with a 20-foot 
putt to regain the lead. Van de Velde, aiming to become the first 
French winner since 1907, went into the final round at even par 
with Parry and Leonard on 5 over. 

</P>
<P>
	Armstrong Remains in Tour Lead  
</P>
<P>
	SAINT-GAUDENS, France (AP) -- Lance Armstrong remained in command  
of the Tour de France today, with Russia's Dimitri Konyshev winning 
the 14th stage as riders reached the foothills of the Pyrenees. 
Armstrong finished in 61st place but retained the yellow jersey he 
has worn the past week. He leads cycling's most famous race by 7 
minutes, 44 second. Armstrong, riding for U.S. Postal Service, won 
the Tour's prologue July 3, a time trial and a grueling mountain 
stage in the Alps. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
