<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swimmer Breaks Breaststroke Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- South African swimmer Penny Heyns set a world  
record in the 100-meter breaststroke Sunday, one day after twice 
breaking the world record in the 200-meter event. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns broke the 100-meter mark with a swim of 1 minute, 6.99  
seconds in the preliminaries of the Janet Evans Invitational at 
USC. She edged the record of 1:07.02, which she set at the 1996 
Olympic finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns, who also holds the world record in the 50-meter  
breaststroke, had a split of 31.73 en route to her mark. 
</P>
<P>
	One day earlier, Heyns set the 100-meter record with a swim of 2  
minutes, 24.69 seconds in the preliminaries. In the finals, she 
lowered the new mark to 2:24.51. 
</P>
<P>
	She broke the record of 2:24.76 set by Australia's Rebecca Brown  
in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns won Olympic gold medals in the 100-meter and 200-meter  
breaststroke in the 1996 Olympics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
