<DOCNO> APW19990718.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 14:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plan Proposed To Reduce Blackouts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Spurred by the recent power blackout in the  
Northeast, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson is proposing a six-part 
plan to better ensure Americans will not lose their electricity 
during severe weather. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is getting worse and in this era of potential  
deregulation in electricity, it is important to protect the 
consumer,'' Richardson said in a telephone interview Sunday from 
Phoenix with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to avert future power crisis, Richardson wants to:  
</P>
<P>
	--Convene a Northeast regional power summit.  
</P>
<P>
	--Investigate power outages.  
</P>
<P>
	--Speed new federal standards for more efficient air  
conditioners. 
</P>
<P>
	--Study the nation's electricity capacity and the ability to meet  
future needs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Cut federal consumption during emergencies.  
</P>
<P>
	--Develop new generation and transmission technologies.  
</P>
<P>
	Richardson intends to outline the strategy in a speech Monday in  
San Francisco to the National Association of Regulatory Utility 
Commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government, the nation's biggest consumer of  
electricity, does not have a general plan for reducing consumption 
during power shortages, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson also is promoting the increased use of alternative  
and renewable energy sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is that some systems are being stretched to the  
limit,'' he says in remarks prepared for delivery Monday. ``Demand 
for electricity continues to grow, while the amount of generating 
and transmission capacity remains stagnant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A heat wave on July 6 resulted in a 19-hour blackout in parts of  
New York City and scattered power losses throughout the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson noted that last year hot weather and capacity  
shortages produced a ``near panic'' in the wholesale market in the 
Midwest, sending power prices to record levels, and that California 
recently experienced record peak demand. 
</P>
<P>
	One pressing problem, he said, is that Washington has not come  
up with legislation to provide federal coordination for the 
deregulation of the electric power industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four states already have adopted electric restructuring  
programs that provide for more competition and consumer choice. But 
other states have put off decisions about new generation and 
transmission resources because of uncertainty about the future of 
federal rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration in April sent Congress a bill aimed at  
removing federal impediments to competition while protecting 
consumer interests. 
</P>
<P>
	Several key members of Congress, including House Commerce  
Committee chairman Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., and Senate Energy and 
Natural Resources Committee Chairman Sen. Frank Murkowski, 
R-Alaska, are working on deregulation legislation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 21:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cat Thief Wins Swaps Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Always a contender this year, Cat Thief  
finally won a race. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief hooked up with General Challenge in a stretch duel and  
won by a head Sunday in the $500,000 Swaps Stakes for 3-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Cat Thief's first victory since October. He had placed in  
five graded events this year, including seconds in the Fountain of 
Youth and Blue Grass Stakes and thirds in the Kentucky and Florida 
derbies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Pat Day, Cat Thief covered 1 1-8 miles in 1:47.87 and  
paid $7.60 and $2.20. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, 11th in the Kentucky Derby, returned $2.10  
under David Flores. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were sitting right where we wanted, it was perfect,''  
Flores said. ``I thought I was going to go by Cat Thief at the 
quarter-pole, but the winner just kept on fighting and just never 
quit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walk That Walk and Corey Nakatani were another 11 lengths back  
in third. Desert Hero, 13th in the Kentucky Derby, was fourth under 
first-time rider Jerry Bailey. There was no show wagering on the 
four-horse field. 
</P>
<P>
	Day sensed something in Cat Thief that the horse hadn't shown  
him in the Fountain of Youth and Florida Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made an excuse for him in the Fountain of Youth because I  
thought maybe he needed the race and had a license to get a little 
tired,'' Day said. ``But in the Florida Derby, when push came to 
shove, he didn't get it done and I felt like there was a little 
more there and he just wasn't giving it to me. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, he was tenacious. I don't think if we'd have gone  
around two more times the other horse was going to get by us,'' Day 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief, who shipped to California from Kentucky in late June,  
prevailed in General Challenge's neighborhood. General Challenge 
came into the race undefeated in five California starts, including 
a 2-for-2 record at Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who would've thought Cat Thief was going to run like that?''  
said Bob Baffert, trainer of General Challenge, who carried high 
weight of 122 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer D. Wayne Lukas set a record with his fourth Swaps  
victory. His others were Victory Speech in 1996, Thunder Gulch in 
1995 and Clear Choice in 1986. He had been tied with Gary Jones at 
three. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a horse race. Pat Day rode him to perfection,'' Lukas  
said by phone from Keeneland, where he's attending the yearling 
sale. ``He was hooked every step of the way by a very good horse 
and still had something left to hold off a very good horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief, who carried 120 pounds, sprinted to the early lead  
and eventually settled along the rail to set up the stretch run. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we had a real good chance going in,'' Lukas said.  
``General Challenge hadn't been able to beat him before. It was a 
very credible performance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge stalked the pace early, put a head in front of  
Cat Thief in midstretch and then continued pressing to the wire. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those races where the fans got their money's worth  
and I didn't get mine,'' Baffert said. ``We just got flat outrun. 
We had every chance to get by and we couldn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The victory, worth $300,000, increased Cat Thief's career  
earnings to $1.1 million, with three wins in 15 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Flores later found the winner's circle in the $300,000 Sunset  
Handicap, scoring an upset with Irish-bred Plicck. The winner paid 
$39.60, $14.60 and $6.60 and covered 1 1/2 miles on the turf in 
2:26.4. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion River Bay was second and paid $4.60 and  
$3.60, while Argentine-bred Lazy Lode was third and returned $4.20 
to show. 
</P>
<P>
	In the $100,000 Hollywood Juvenile Championship, Dixie Union and  
Alex Solis won by 1 1/4 lengths over Exchange Rate in 1:09.95 for six 
furlongs. The winner paid $3.40, $2.20 and $2.10 and is owned by 
Herman Sarkowsky, former co-owner of the Seattle Seahawks and 
Portland Trail Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	Love That Red won the $100,000 Answer Do Stakes by 1 1/4 lengths  
over Men's Exclusive. The winner covered 6 1/2 furlongs in 1:15.06 and 
paid $4.80, $2.60 and $2.10. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 21:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
