<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 23:30:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> America Awaits Word on Kennedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Once again, America was waiting.  
</P>
<P>
	This weekend, rescuers and investigators looked for a sign -- any  
sign -- of John F. Kennedy Jr.: A fragment of his missing plane. A 
beep from the aircraft's emergency beacon. A piece of luggage 
floating on the light chop of the waters off Martha's Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
	But the answers didn't come right away. And as the search for  
JFK Jr., his wife and her sister stretched through Saturday, then 
Sunday, the anguish of Americans around the country deepened. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, almost exactly 48 hours since the moment his aircraft  
vanished off radar screens at 9:40 p.m. Friday, a Coast Guard rear 
admiral in starched white uniform confirmed the worst fears of 
Americans: that the son of the fallen president likely was dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``This incident brings back vivid memories of the wait that we  
were involved in after Bobby was shot that night in Los Angeles,'' 
said Rep. Johnny Ford, D-Alabama, one of Robert F. Kennedy's 
political strategists who witnessed his assassination during the 
1968 presidential campaign.. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most difficult thing for all of us was the wait. That's  
what we're going through again ... The Kennedy Wait.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It has, for America, become an agonizingly familiar ritual: On  
Nov. 22, 1963, the nation could only watch and wait as President 
John F. Kennedy slipped away after being shot in Dallas. Then, five 
years later, it did the same as the former president's brother died 
from bullet wounds in California. 
</P>
<P>
	And now, across the United States, it was happening again --  
Americans waiting for bitter news about a Kennedy. This time, it 
was about the man who, as America's first son, a three-year-old in 
blue coat and shorts, poignantly saluted his father's casket in 
1963. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all watched him grow up through the TV and when something  
like this happens, it happens to all of us,'' said Frank Lopez, a 
furniture truck driver who came from the New York borough of Queens 
with his mother, Lucy, to leave an American flag and flowers at the 
door to Kennedy's Manhattan apartment block. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kennedys, he added, ``are part of America, and they show  
Americans what they could be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Early Sunday, people prayed for Kennedy and his family at Our  
Lady of Victory Church in Hyannis Port, Mass., where the Kennedys 
sometimes worship while staying at their nearby compound. 
</P>
<P>
	Noreen Sacca, on her way home from the beach, stopped at the  
John F. Kennedy Library and Museum in Boston. She found bouquets of 
flowers left on the museum grounds. ``I've been to church twice to 
pray for them all,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	More bouquets of red carnations and a votive candle were left on  
the front lawn of the home in Brookline, Mass., where President 
Kennedy was born. A National Park Service ranger repeated words 
written in 1970 for the autobiography of the family's matriarch, 
Rose Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``She says that her children were blessed with many gifts --  
beauty, intelligence, the ability to inspire respect, and make 
friends, but God held one gift back, and that's their length of 
years,'' David F. Kratz said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Kennedy burial plot at Arlington National Cemetery,  
several hundred people endured a heat wave to honor father and son. 
Laurie Krahn, a tourist from Michigan, said Kennedy's disappearance 
was ``very sobering. ... I'm just terribly saddened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When workers arrived Sunday morning at the Dallas museum in the  
building from which President Kennedy was shot, they found a small 
flower arrangement wedged in the doorway. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff West, director of the Sixth Floor Museum in the former  
Texas School Book Depository, looked out a window and saw a woman 
stop her car and lay flowers at the site of the historic marker in 
Dealey Plaza. Another woman walked up with her husband, paused and 
laid cut gladiolas at the site. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's heartbreaking. It gets to you,'' West said.  
</P>
<P>
	Only 50 people live on Cumberland Island, the coastal barrier  
island off Georgia where JFK Jr. wed Carolyn Bessette in 1996, by 
the light of a flashlight inside a small, wood-framed church built 
by the descendents of slaves. 
</P>
<P>
	But the helplessness, sorrow and sense of loss were no less  
felt. 
</P>
<P>
	``For those of us who shared John and Caroline's friendship and  
wedding, we'd like to express our grief and deep sadness,'' said 
Zachary Zoul, manager of the 17-room Greyfield Inn where Kennedy 
reception was held. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will remain in the hearts of all of us on Cumberland  
Island forever.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
