<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Keeneland Horse Sales Set for Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Yearlings from the cream of the 1998 foal  
crop, including five by the late great Mr. Propsector, go on the 
auction block starting Monday at Keeneland's annual sale of elite 
colts and fillies. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, the two-day sale is expected to draw spirited bidding  
from the world's top thoroughbred owners and trainers, with no hint 
that the strong spending of recent years will slow. 
</P>
<P>
	``All indications are that it's going to be very good,'' said  
Duncan Taylor, president of Taylor Made Sales Agency, one of the 
largest consigners of yearlings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Racing's getting good exposure, they had a record crowd at  
Belmont, the stock market's stayed good. All the indicators are 
good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, buyers spent an average of $482,765 on 149 horses,  
with 15 going for $1 million or more and 56 fetching $500,000 or 
more -- all levels of spending not seen since the mid-to-late 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year was the fourth straight in which the average price  
paid for a Keeneland July yearling was up. The average price was 
the highest since 1985 and the median price of $360,000 was the 
highest ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the bidders driving last year's big numbers were Satish  
Sanan's Padua Stables and the European-based Coolmore partnership 
of Michael Tabor and John Magnier. Together, Coolmore and Padua 
accounted for 11 of the $1 million yearlings and 30.5 percent of 
the money spent at the sale, and both are back for this year's 
sale. 
</P>
<P>
	They will find plenty of well-bred yearlings on which to bid.  
</P>
<P>
	The second-to-last crop from Mr. Prospector, euthanized last  
month at age 29, includes a colt who is a half-brother to Belmont 
winner Editor's Note and a colt out of Seattle Slew daughter 
Embellished. 
</P>
<P>
	And Arthur Hancock's Stone Farm will see if it can strike gold  
for the second year in a row with a son of Mr. Prospector out of 
the mare Angel Fever. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Hancock topped the sale with a Mr. Propsector-Angel  
Fever colt that sold for $4 million, the highest Keeneland summer 
sale price since Seattle Dancer went for a record $13.1 million in 
1985. Sanan and the Coolmore operation joined forces in an attempt 
to buy that colt, but lost out to Japanese horseman Fusao 
Sekiguchi. 
</P>
<P>
	The two Mr. Prospector fillies in this year's sale are Serena's  
Tune, a daughter of 3-year-old champion filly Serena's Song, winner 
of 11 graded stakes and $3.3 million in her career, and a yearling 
out of Fit For A Queen. 
</P>
<P>
	The sires with the most horses cataloged are Gone West, with 14,  
1992 Belmont winner A.P. Indy and Irish champion Woodman, with 13 
each, and two-time leading sire Deputy Minister, with 12. 
</P>
<P>
	The last two Triple Crown winners, Seattle Slew (1977) and  
Affirmed (1978), each have yearlings in the sale, while young sires 
Grindstone, Hennessy and Smart Strike each will have foals from 
their first crop up for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	All but 11 of the yearlings cataloged for the sale were bred in  
Kentucky, and only one was bred outside North America, a chestnut 
colt by Forty Niner out of World Glory, who was foaled in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale opens with a session Monday evening and concludes with  
sessions Tuesday afternoon and evening. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
