<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> News Media Seize on Kennedy Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- TV stuck with a story that for many anxious  
hours yielded few new facts -- then, Sunday evening, gave up its 
tragic outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	At a broadcast briefing shortly after 9:30 p.m. EDT, Coast Guard  
Rear Adm. Richard Larrabee left no hope for John F. Kennedy Jr., 
his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and his sister-in-law Lauren 
Bessette, whose plane went down off the Massachusetts coast Friday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Transportation Safety Board, said Larrabee in a  
grim voice, ``could not be too optimistic about survival.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Already, the nation's three newsweeklies had busted deadlines  
and remade their issues to put John F. Kennedy Jr. on the cover. 
</P>
<P>
	Time, U.S. News and World Report, and Newsweek were due on  
newsstands Monday after scrambling to focus on the tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We pretty much redid the whole edition,'' said Newsweek  
spokesman Roy Brunett. Of its 55 editorial pages, 29 were devoted 
to the cover package of stories, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	People magazine, which in 1988 anointed Kennedy ``The Sexiest  
Man Alive,'' also gave him the cover in its next issue, out this 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, John F. Kennedy Jr. is extremely popular with our  
readers, so we'll give this the attention it deserves,'' 
spokeswoman Susan Ollinick said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday newspapers devoted page after page to coverage of the  
search. While The New York Times placed the story on the left-hand, 
secondary spot on its front page, The Washington Post ran the 
banner headline ``JFK Jr. Feared Dead in Plane Crash,'' and the New 
York Post cried, ``MORE TEARS.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the day, while the nation was watching, listening and  
reading, many also spoke up. On Sunday afternoon, America Online 
logged one message posted every second concerning the Kennedy 
disappearance. That's comparable to the response after Princess 
Diana's death in 1997, said spokeswoman Regina Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are mostly well-wishers and prayers and  
I-remember-when,'' Lewis said from AOL headquarters in Dulles, Va. 
``Not everyone has a newspaper column, and as people are digesting 
this, they want to say something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox all concentrated on the Kennedy tragedy on  
their Sunday morning news programs, and cable's CNN, Fox News 
Channel and MSNBC stayed with the story throughout. 
</P>
<P>
	But until late in the day, most of what viewers found was  
rehashed information, recapped family history and what often 
sounded like eulogies -- even before the worst was conceded. 
</P>
<P>
	``He makes a real point of introducing himself,'' said George  
Stephanopolous on ABC's ``This Week,'' praising Kennedy in the 
present tense as a regular guy. But a few moments later, he sadly 
spoke of sister Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg: ``Now she's lost her 
entire immediate family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From hovering helicopters, the networks beamed pictures of Coast  
Guard search efforts off Martha's Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
	They also relied on their news archives, which chronicle the man  
called ``the nation's favorite son'' all the way back to a 1960 
newsreel of him leaving the hospital at 13 days old with his mother 
and president-elect father. 
</P>
<P>
	Other footage showed Kennedy and his wife of slightly less than  
three years -- a golden couple who commanded the world's attention. 
</P>
<P>
	The TV vigil seemed eerily familiar to Bob Schieffer, anchor of  
CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Every so often,'' he said, ``almost as if on schedule,  
something happens to the Kennedys and we gather around our 
television sets to watch them deal with yet another unspeakable 
grief.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
