<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Megamall Builder Eyes Calif., Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Megamall developer Mills Corp. is targeting  
California and Europe in an ambitious plan that seeks to dot the 
landscape of two continents with entertainment-oriented shopping 
centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Best known for building huge, suburban malls such as Ontario  
Mills near Los Angeles, the company has profitably ridden a 
retailing trend that aims to court shoppers by combining discount 
retail shops with upscale restaurants and entertainment centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Based in Arlington, Va., Mills has taken the entertainment side  
of that equation beyond video arcades to trout-fishing ponds, 
skateboard parks and even a BMX dirt-bike trail in malls in 
California, Pennsylvania, Texas, Florida, Arizona, Illinois, 
Wisconsin and the District of Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Mills wants to apply that same formula to open-air plazas  
in U.S. and European cities. In Europe, the company is looking at 
sites in Spain and Northern Italy. In California, potential sites 
include downtown Los Angeles and the San Francisco area. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans for the European and downtown Los Angeles projects are  
still in the formulative stages, but Mills executives believe 
European and American shoppers share an attraction to shopping 
spiced with entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where we think retailing is going,'' Laurence C.  
Siegel, Mills chairman and chief executive officer, said in an 
interview. ``It's got to be interactive. It's got to be fun. 
Shopping has got to be exciting. If it's not, just turn on the 
computer and buy it online.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Mills opened the $165 million Block at Orange, an  
open-air shopping plaza in suburban Orange, Calif. The company's 
first open-air development, the Block is smaller than Mills' indoor 
malls, and features upscale stores instead of discount outlets, but 
it shares the same emphasis on entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	With modifications, the concept could work in Europe, said  
Stanley Eichelbaum, president of the consulting firm Marketing 
Developments Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``With refinement, it has potential just about throughout the  
world,'' said Eichelbaum, whose company is developing similar 
projects in Central America and the Middle East. ``Worldwide 
there's a desire, especially in the aging portions of the world, 
for the nostalgia of the streetside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Europe, in particular, is naturally suited to Siegel's vision  
because retailing never moved indoors, as it did in the United 
States during the 1960s and 1970s. A few indoor malls based on the 
American model have been built in Europe, but the concept hasn't 
caught on, said Eichelbaum. 
</P>
<P>
	In downtown Los Angeles, Siegel wants to build an upscale  
outdoor shopping plaza that would include a hotel and office space. 
Construction of the plaza would be good news for downtown, which 
already appears on its way to renewal with plans for a basketball 
arena, the Roman Catholic archdiocese's new cathedral and the $255 
million Disney Concert Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the sound you hear of the dam bursting in terms of  
interest in downtown,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the 
Los Angeles County Economic Development Corp. ``The standard line 
is downtown is still a troubled area, but you've got to look longer 
range because there's a tremendous amount of money being spent on 
downtown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The concept of mixing entertainment and retail is not unique to  
Mills, but the company has done a good job of attracting top names 
in both industries to its malls. In some cases, Mills has worked 
with companies such as Saks Fifth Avenue to make their first 
venture in the outlet arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Discount outlets featured at Mills megamalls include Reebok,  
Samsonite, Calvin Klein, Donna Karan, Nordstrom and Neiman Marcus. 
Entertainment venues include companies like Dave &AMP; Buster's and 
GameWorks. 
</P>
<P>
	Typically, the huge malls averaging 1.7 million square feet,  
such as Ontario Mills, are built 15 to 40 miles outside a major 
metropolitan area. 
</P>
<P>
	Three more are under construction in Nashville, Concord, N.C.,  
and Katy, Texas. Eventually, Siegel wants to build another 30 
across the United States. The company already has picked sites in 
Georgia, New Jersey, Maryland, Massachusetts, California and 
Ontario, Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for Mills, a real estate investment trust, rose 9  
percent to $45.6 million during 1999's first quarter. Earnings 
before an extraordinary item were up 25 percent to $10.8 million, 
thanks to higher lease rates and increased mall occupancy levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of their malls are very, very popular with the public,''  
said Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report. ``By 
and large this is the day and age for companies such as Mills.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
