<HEADLINE> Aldrin Glad Armstrong Was First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Apollo 11 astronaut Buzz Aldrin said Sunday that  
he has no regrets that Neil Armstrong stepped on the moon ahead of 
him 30 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, who became the first man to walk on the moon on July  
20, 1969, was chosen because of seniority, said Aldrin, who touched 
the moon moments later. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was rather relieved that it was decided that particular way  
because I didn't have to respond to all sort of questions about 
what am I going to say when I get on the moon,'' said Aldrin in a 
British Broadcasting Corp. interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has had to take the attention of the world as the first man  
to be on the surface of the moon,'' said Aldrin. ``And that has a 
considerable impact on a person's life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aldrin, who was visiting London in conjunction with the  
celebration of the anniversary of the moon landing, said civilians 
should go into space. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about time that ordinary people be given the  
opportunity,'' he said. ``I don't see why we don't start by taking 
a journalist up before the (2000 presidential) election.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
