<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spouses of Some Reps. Spurn DC Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic Rep. Bart Stupak of Michigan  
gathered his belongings and moved to the nation's capital after his 
election in 1992. His family stayed home. 
</P>
<P>
	Stupak and his wife Laurie, a councilwoman in their hometown of  
Menominee, already had agreed she and their two sons would not 
follow if he won. 
</P>
<P>
	``We figured that we would be apart either way and that it was  
better for us, better for the family, if the kids and I would 
remain in the district,'' said Laurie Stupak, now the mayor. ``It 
was less destructive to our family life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stupaks are hardly an anomaly. More and more, lawmakers'  
spouses are staying in their home states instead of moving to 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Children, careers or contempt for the city keep some away, while  
lawmakers' regular weekend visits back to the district encourage 
others to stay put. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just don't move to Washington like they did,'' said  
Sandie Knollenberg, president of the Republican Congressional 
Spouses Club and wife of four-term Rep. Joseph Knollenberg, R-Mich. 
``That's been changing with the advent of working women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the congressional spouses are a television news anchor  
(Deborah Knapp Bonilla, wife of Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas); the 
president of the National First Ladies' Library (Mary Regula, wife 
of Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio); the chief executive officer of 
Washington's leading public broadcasting station (Sharon Percy 
Rockefeller, wife of Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.); and the 
chairman of RIF, a national literacy advocacy group (Lynda Johnson 
Robb, wife of Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va.) 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really become a very challenging issue, and I don't think  
there's any good answer,'' said Debbie Dingell, married to longtime 
Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich. ``It's very hard for spouses and 
families to travel back and forth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As reasons for the trend, she cited the pressure on members to  
be with their constituents and the difficulties of travel for 
spouses. Congress does not provide travel allowances for families, 
nor can spouses travel at government rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dingell, president of General Motors' philanthropic arm,  
observed that she also has begun to spend more time in Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm John's eyes and ears in the district. I'm working there. I  
grocery shop there,'' she said. ``In many ways, the family keeps in 
touch with everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some husbands live outside of Washington, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Larry Lehrner, a kidney specialist, wed freshman Rep.  
Shelley Berkley, D-Nev., in May but stayed in Las Vegas because of 
the practice he shares with three endocrinologists and six other 
kidney doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tell people that she has three reasons to come home every  
weekend,'' he said: ``First to see her two kids, second to see her 
constituents and third to see me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such arrangements generally are not the norm for senators, who  
usually are older, have grown children and serve longer terms -- six 
years vs. two years for House members. There are a few senatorial 
exceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Maine GOP Sen. Olympia Snowe's husband, John McKernan Jr., the  
state's former governor, runs two companies based in Portland. 
Democratic Sen. Patty Murray's family returned to Seattle in 1995 
during her first term. 
</P>
<P>
	Some believe the dwindling physical presence of families and  
social opportunities in lawmakers' lives hurts interpersonal 
relations in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Families are the softening and the glue,'' said Mrs. Dingell.  
</P>
<P>
	Others said it would help Congress function better. ``It's hard  
to fight with your friends,'' said Mrs. Knollenberg, adding that 
families could benefit by moving to Washington. ``You will 
disagree, but you will do it in a nicer way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dawn Gibbons said she tried life in Washington but returned to  
Reno, Nev., after three months. She blamed it on too many lonely 
Washington weekends with their son while her husband, GOP Rep. 
James Gibbons, went home to his constituents. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just can't pick up an 11-year-old and go back and forth,''  
Mrs. Gibbons, a Nevada assemblywoman, explained. She said moving 
was ``kind of a shocker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept thinking, `What is normal here?''' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Stupak had been on the Menominee, Mich., city council for  
several years when her husband won the first of his four House 
terms. She stayed to fulfill her commitment to the city and to keep 
their sons in the same schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's worked very well for us that way,'' she said.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
