<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Union Hiring 2,000 Tellers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Banking giant First Union Corp. is hiring  
2,000 tellers in an admission it's misjudged how much customers 
want to see real people for their banking needs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Charlotte bank began the effort a few months ago and has  
hired about 1,000 tellers. First Union spokeswoman Allison Rash 
said Friday the bank now plans to hire at least 1,000 more tellers. 
Plans are to hire an undetermined additional number of sales 
specialists for the branches, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The news comes after about 5,800 First Union workers were laid  
off in March. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union, which upset investors by twice reducing quarterly  
earnings estimates this year, laid off employees and cut costs in 
an effort to boost profits. The bank has struggled to absorb 
acquisitions including Philadelphia's CoreStates Financial Corp. 
and finance company The Money Store. 
</P>
<P>
	Only about 2 percent of those laid off this year came from the  
bank's Future Bank branches, Rash said. 
</P>
<P>
	Future Bank is a First Union concept that relies heavily on  
technology such as personal computers, ATMs, the Internet and 
telephones to use fewer employees in each branch. Many of the 
employees rotate between a group of branches. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank sent many of the extra workers displaced by the concept  
to a central calling office in Charlotte. Now First Union 
management has found that even though customers don't need to come 
into a branch, they come in anyway and demand service. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is we value our customer relationships,'' Rash  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision was well received by analysts.  
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Cohn, an analyst with Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. said he thought  
the bank was just ``overzealous'' in their cost-cutting efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did they manage this process properly? The answer is obviously  
not. It cost them money to lay people off. It's going to cost them 
again to hire people. Did they waste a lot of money in here? 
Absolutely,'' Cohn said. ``On the other hand it's an ongoing 
business and you've got to handle the business. They made a mistake 
and they recognize it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
