<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bookseller Collects Used Volumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The five dogs in John King's office are castoffs  
that lost an ear or an owner before landing in his care. 
</P>
<P>
	The canines fit neatly into King's secondhand empire of rare and  
used books. They get the same tender care and benefit from the same 
rule against throwing away anything of value, a rule that has 
allowed King to turn his collection, John K. King Books, into one 
of the nation's largest. 
</P>
<P>
	``John has that rescuer bent to him,'' says the store's  
assistant manager, Thomas Heitjan. ``He picks the dogs up off the 
street, the books that have no home, and the employees too. A lot 
of us couldn't find jobs in the real world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King's world includes as many as 1 million books housed in a  
converted glove factory, filling four stories in an industrial area 
near downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	To it he draws customers ranging from wealthy bibliophiles to  
the merely curious. Aaron Stepien, of Dearborn, visits the 
bookstore about once a month. ``I come in with the intention of 
getting one or two books, and I end up leaving with a stack,'' he 
says. ``There's really no reason to go anywhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King, who will only put his age in the late 40s, quit college to  
pursue his passion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some kids hang out at the graveyard. They become gravediggers.  
Some kids hang out at the dope dens. They become dope dealers. I 
hung out at used bookstores,'' he says. ``I respected the things I 
read. It was information that other people didn't have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King, a balding man with blond ringlets bumping his collar,  
roams the store and his office building behind it with a 
walkie-talkie and a bottle of Mountain Dew. The dozen or so staff 
members rely on walkie-talkies to find each other, allowing King to 
proudly claim ``the only radio-dispatched used bookstore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The store's exterior is worn like a battered paperback, and a  
soapy light seeps through plastic-covered windows onto hundreds of 
shelves 6 1/2 feet high -- enough to stretch four miles, King 
estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of the concrete floor sport a '70s vintage pea-green  
carpet mended with duct tape. Milk crates from defunct dairies 
serve as storage bins and footstools. There's not a chromed 
espresso machine in sight. ``I don't want people spilling coffee 
all over the books,'' King says. 
</P>
<P>
	He also says he sells about a million books a year. Customers  
include other collectors as well as decorators who want the 
solemnity of books bound in leather. 
</P>
<P>
	On one typical spring day, Linda Snide of Lincoln Park roamed  
the fiction area. Like many other customers, Snide has her own 
collection that she supplements with regular visits to King's 
store. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a book person,'' she says. ``I never fall asleep without a  
book. I love the textures, the smells of books, the feel of books. 
This is the perfect place to be. I could lose myself for a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth Schubert and her brother, Bob Chase, browsed the cookbook  
section. Both are avid collectors in their own right -- Ms. 
Schubert, 80, has already arranged for her collection to go to 
Harvard when she dies. 
</P>
<P>
	Chase, who lives in Florida, calls King's prices and arrangement  
superior. ``We're usually satisfied if we walk into a bookstore and 
they have this many,'' he says, lining off about a third of the 
books King has on the topic. ``It's just sheer volume.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King's office doubles as a showroom for rare and collectible  
books -- a much more presentable space full of gilded volumes, 
prints and history's flotsam. 
</P>
<P>
	About twice a year he publishes a catalog of his rare goods --  
not just books, but documents and photos, such as a signed 1941 
letter from Adolf Hitler to an officer. 
</P>
<P>
	His oldest book dates to 1478. The most expensive, a first  
edition of Samuel Johnson's English dictionary, lists for $12,500. 
Among the rarities is a limited edition of James Joyce's 
``Ulysses'' autographed by the illustrator, Henri Matisse, and 20 
or so books with ``fore-edge'' paintings on the vertical edges of 
the pages. 
</P>
<P>
	King and his crew scour other stores and estate sales, looking  
for bargains. Many people offer the store the odd collection of a 
deceased relative passionately interested in engineering, 
volunteering, mountaineering. Those discoveries are the kind King 
cherishes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like buying books from some warehouse,'' he says.  
``It's people who picked the books and read them and lived with 
them and learned from them. All their philosophies and all their 
thoughts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King relies on thousands of reference books for setting prices,  
and the research often pays for itself. The store once bought a 
book signed and dated by Carl Sandburg and Sinclair Lewis to 
someone named ``Gene.'' A quick check of Lewis' biography found 
that on the same date, the two writers visited socialist leader 
Eugene V. Debs in prison -- and King could double the book's price. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's wonderful to know so many people throughout history  
signed a book, or touched a book,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the advent of the Internet, he says, that wonder is  
supporting fewer and fewer businesses. Now, King says, any ``scummy 
guy'' with a computer can check out the prices and information from 
a professional, then put his own goods online at lower prices 
without paying for the research -- or getting it right. 
</P>
<P>
	The store does put its rare-book catalog online and sells one to  
two books a day that way. Though King understands the challenge of 
his online competition, he has no plans to expand his Internet 
sales. He doesn't even want computers in his office -- preferring to 
collect IBM Selectric typewriters, kept near mementos of the 
now-defunct bookstores he roamed as a teen-ager. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
