<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reagan Had Pen Pal for 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A dozen lines Ronald Reagan scribbled from the  
set of a World War II propaganda movie in response to a fan letter 
from a 13-year-old Philadelphia girl began a pen pal relationship 
that lasted half a century. 
</P>
<P>
	As described in The New Yorker magazine, Reagan's letters  
offered intimate insights into his many incarnations: B-movie actor 
to Truman Democrat to labor activist to conservative politician to 
the president who chiseled his own chunk of mortar from the Berlin 
Wall. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine reports in the issue on newsstands Monday that  
Reagan's pen pal, Lorraine Wagner, saved 276 of Reagan's letters 
and cards and recently sold them to a Philadelphia-area autograph 
dealer, Steven Raab. The New Yorker said she wants the collection 
to end up in the Ronald Reagan Presidential Library in California. 
</P>
<P>
	The letters dealt candidly with both personal and professional  
matters -- both ups and downs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan wrote of his desire to work out his marital problems  
with actress Jane Wyman, his first wife. ``Janie is still a pretty 
sick girl in mind, but I'm still hoping that things will be 
different when she gets over this nervousness,'' he wrote in answer 
to 18-year-old Lorraine's 1948 question about divorce rumors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--In the same year, he wrote of his great hopes for the country  
after Harry S. Truman's upset victory in the presidential election. 
``I'm sure Truman, with a Democratic congress, will do lots to make 
things better in every way, and what a landslide it was for him, 
the votes boy!'' 
</P>
<P>
	--The future president exulted at an impending visit to Los  
Angeles in 1950 by Lorraine and a Brooklyn, N.Y., friend, the 
international president of Reagan's fan club. ``Boy oh boy, wait 
till you see (the ranch) I bought,'' Reagan wrote. ``It's a honey, 
a great big ranch nearer the Ocean, swimming pool and everything. I 
feel like a kid with a new toy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--He kept a stiff upper lip when his movie career waned as  
younger actors became a new kind of leading man and he was 
relegated to fronting for a Las Vegas variety show. Doing casino 
monologues, he wrote to his friend in 1954, was like ``going over 
`Niagara Falls' in a tub,'' but ``the show is going over real 
big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letters even touched on the mundane, such as his distaste of  
English weather. After filming World War II drama ``The Hasty 
Heart'' in ``damp foggy'' England in 1949, he wrote that he never 
wanted to work there again. ``Was I ever happy to reach the old 
USA. I hope I can stay in California the rest of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After becoming active in Republican politics, Reagan used  
Lorraine and her husband -- she married Navy veteran Elwood Wagner 
in 1954 -- to learn the candid perspectives of a middle-class 
American family, The New Yorker said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1964 election, he repeatedly wrote of the merits of  
Arizona Sen. Barry Goldwater, the GOP presidential candidate 
against President Johnson. Mrs. Wagner turned from leaning toward 
Johnson to voting for Goldwater, then jokingly chided Reagan for 
brainwashing her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't agree that you have been brainwashed,'' he wrote two  
days after the election. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do agree that you kept an open mind, looked at both sides  
and made a personal decision in the finest example of the tradition 
of our democracy. If we are to continue having freedom, it will be 
because of people like yourselves and not those who are just 
blindly going down the road, voting on the basis of who makes the 
most attractive promise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the last few years of their correspondence -- it ended in 1995  
with the announcement that Reagan has Alzheimer's disease -- Reagan 
often spoke of his pleasure at the fall of communism and the end of 
the Cold War. He wrote of his thrill at having lived to see the 
Berlin Wall torn down and, on a trip to Eastern Europe in 1990, how 
he carried a hammer to the wall and chiseled off his own chunk. 
</P>
<P>
	The relationship began with a fan letter from a teen-ager to a  
movie star, answered as Reagan took a break from shooting Irving 
Berlin's ``This Is the Army.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It ended 52 years later, when 65-year-old Mrs. Wagner received  
the same farewell message from Reagan that was sent to thousands of 
friends to tell them of his Alzheimer's. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 13:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> JFK Jr., Diana Remain in Their Prime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Their easy smiles and their glamorous lifestyles catapulted them  
to an unparalleled upper tier of fame -- a perch unusual even for 
this celebrity-obsessed nation. Somehow, these two were different. 
</P>
<P>
	She was an actual princess; he was the closest thing this  
country had to a prince. America's tragedy was his personal loss; 
her private trials became public obsessions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It kind of seems like Princess Diana all over again,'' said  
Melissa Monahan, 23, of Dumont, N.J., visiting the flower-festooned 
stoop outside John F. Kennedy Jr.'s lower Manhattan loft Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Diana and JFK Jr., whose superstar allure made them objects of  
desire, whose sorrows made them seem accessible, lived different 
lives under very different circumstances. Yet each of them -- tragic 
young people who lived well and were lost abruptly -- represents the 
pinnacle of enduring celebrity. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a 20th-century phenomenon, driven by movies, television and  
now cyberspace, born with the likes of Rudolph Valentino and Jean 
Harlow, refined with James Dean and Marilyn Monroe. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood created the star machine; then the rest of the world  
went Hollywood. During the tumult of the 1960s, Jack and Bobby 
Kennedy, Malcolm X and the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. became a new 
kind of celebrity that blended achievement and allure. Their 
assassinations ensured it would last forever. 
</P>
<P>
	Not so for many young superstars, who tarnish with age. The  
corpulent Marlon Brando will never eclipse the forever lanky Dean, 
and Monroe has far more staying power than an Alzheimer's-stricken 
Rita Hayworth ever will. 
</P>
<P>
	Now JFK Jr. and Diana are frozen in that video-age amber, their  
legacy an archive's worth of images ready for eternal playback on 
TV and the Net, showing them forever in their prime, the ordinary 
and the extraordinary in one slick package. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're living in a time when the machines of mythology are more  
powerful and pervasive than ever,'' said Art Simon, author of 
``Dangerous Knowledge: The JFK Assassination in Art and Film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Diana and JFK Jr. were easy sells, examples of historian  
Daniel J. Boorstin's 1961 definition of celebrity as ``someone 
known for their well-knownness.'' They sold well: Diana has been on 
the cover of People magazine 50 times, JFK Jr. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	The lovely Diana was the ideal royalty for a talk-show culture  
that demands accessibility with its pipe dreams. She was divorced. 
She fought bulimia. Her blemishes showed through the glitz but 
never overshadowed it. Her mother-in-law, the queen, traveled in 
limos; Diana kissed AIDS patients. 
</P>
<P>
	JFK Jr.'s very lineage ensured him a place. He was the namesake  
and most visible vestige of Camelot, of a time and a presidency 
that may not have been innocent but is remembered that way. 
</P>
<P>
	But while his parents were patricians who appealed to common  
folk, he was a self-styled commoner who, though a Kennedy, favored 
Rollerblading around his neighborhood and throwing Frisbees around 
Central Park. Jackie Onassis might well sweep into the Four Seasons 
behind oversized sunglasses; her son favored breakfast at Bubby's, 
a corner restaurant in his Tribeca neighborhood. Like Diana, he 
stooped to conquer, and it was captivating. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was saying to myself, 'Why are you feeling like it was your  
loss? Why is it so painful?''' said Lavonne Smith, 43, of Chicago. 
``That's the way it was with Princess Di -- all weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, people said, he was a celebrity, but so many likened him to  
a little brother or a son or a regular guy. He seemed the nation's 
property: They took his father away, people said, so he belonged to 
us. Much like the language that British and Americans alike used 
when Diana died. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the times that we see them, they're doing something  
that Joe American would do,'' said Matt Hogge, a 24-year-old 
chemical engineer from Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, JFK Jr. was never one of us; he was the son of a mythic  
president just as 17-year-old Prince William is the son of a real 
princess who will spend his life living up to her memory. In an 
interview just before her death in an August 1997 car crash, Diana 
suggested the younger Kennedy's approach to fame might be a useful 
model for her son, a future king. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want William to be able to handle things as well as John  
does,'' she told The New Yorker. 
</P>
<P>
	Then she died, and joined the ranks of the famous who never grow  
old, who become blank slates for an endless list of dreams. 
</P>
<P>
	``With both of them, there was so much room to project and  
imagine anything you wanted,'' said Simon, the author. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could project a future political candidate. You could  
project a great lover and romancer of women. You could project a 
down-to-earth guy. You could write a dozen biographies without even 
knowing the guy,'' Simon said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a way, he's a receptacle for a lot of fantasies. That's  
what Diana was, too. And that may be the perfect definition of the 
ultimate celebrity.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990718.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 14:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Frenchman Collapses at British Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Jean Van de Velde teetered on the  
brink of collapse the entire British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	When it finally came, it was spectacular.  
</P>
<P>
	In a bizarre 18th hole performance that had spectators covering  
their eyes in anguish, Van de Velde went from sure winner to 
eventual playoff loser in seven shocking strokes. 
</P>
<P>
	Needing only a double bogey to win, the Frenchman who had made  
so many miraculous saves all week unraveled in a shocking 
combination of bad shots and poor decisions. Thousands crowding the 
18th green could only murmur in sympathy. 
</P>
<P>
	Wielding a 2-iron to finish in style when he should have been  
laying up to protect a lead, Van de Velde blew a three-stroke lead 
on the final hole to cost him the title he was never supposed to 
win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't even go for the glory. That wasn't even glory,'' Van  
de Velde said. ``That wasn't something absolutely bad I was trying 
to do. You know, it just came out to be a nightmare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The engraver had already started putting Van de Velde's name on  
the championship claret jug when it all disintegrated in the space 
of 487 torturous yards. 
</P>
<P>
	It may have been the greatest collapse in major championship  
golf history. It was certainly the most stunning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I blew it on 18,'' Van de Velde said. ``But there are  
worse things in life. Some terrible things are happening to other 
people. It's only a golf tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A hole that began innocently enough with a pushed tee shot spun  
out of control with a horrible decision to go for the green with a 
2-iron from 189 yards instead of laying up safely with a pitching 
wedge and then going for the green in three from the fairway. 
</P>
<P>
	It ended with Van de Velde needing to sink an 8-footer for a  
triple bogey seven just to get into the playoff won by Paul Lawrie. 
</P>
<P>
	In between, Van de Velde hit a grandstand and he hit it in the  
water. He hit it into the deep rough and he hacked it into a 
greenside bunker. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could see him just throwing the tournament away,'' playing  
partner Craig Parry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde even climbed down the rock wall of the Barry Burn,  
stripped his shoes and socks off, and contemplated a miracle shot 
from the water. It seemed as if he was determined to go up in 
flames, but by the time he got down to the ball the water had risen 
and he abandoned that idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could see the ball sinking and saying, `Not for you  
today,''' Van de Velde said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a chaotic end to a round Van de Velde had somehow held  
together with the magic of his putter while only hitting five 
fairways. 
</P>
<P>
	As he stepped on the tee, he saw 487 yards of terror, with deep  
rough on the left and a ditch known as the Barry Burn snaking its 
way down both sides of the hole and in front of the green. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also could have hit wedges all the way down the hole and  
still won. He only needed six, not four. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next time, maybe I'll hit the wedge and you will all forgive  
me,'' Van de Velde said. ``I knew all I needed was a five or six. 
But one thing you learn in golf, though, is nothing is done until 
you make the last putt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde pulled out a driver, his first bad decision, but  
one that didn't hurt after the ball came to rest right of the 
fairway on a grass peninsula surrounded by the Barry Burn. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the decision that cost him the tournament. His 2-iron  
was pushed and headed for the grandstand, hitting it and bouncing 
back off the rock wall of the Barry Burn about 50 yards from the 
green. 
</P>
<P>
	The ditch was still between him and the green, though, and his  
third shot, a wedge, barely got out of the deep rough and plopped 
into the water. 
</P>
<P>
	After going into the ditch barefoot, with water up to his  
calves, Van de Velde dropped back in the rough and hit again, now 
his fifth shot with the penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	This one landed in the greenside bunker, where Parry already was  
in two. Parry hit next, holing his shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``What about you following me into the hole?'' he asked Van de  
Velde. 
</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde didn't, but knocked it about eight feet away. He  
then calmly stepped up and made the put, shaking his fist in a 
combination of anger and relief. He yelled at the offending ball, 
then heaved it into the water it had just come from. 
</P>
<P>
	There was still a playoff ahead, but Van de Velde was done. It  
showed when he hit a horrendous drive off the first playoff hole 
deep into a thicket of bushes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took me awhile to swallow it,'' he said. ``I hit a shocking  
drive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde's wife, Brigitte, who had followed him the entire  
day, was standing on a milkbox to peer over the crowd as her 
husband fell apart. 
</P>
<P>
	The advice she had wanted to give him at lunch that day but  
didn't dare say would have proved helpful. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was thinking if you have a one- or two-shot lead, don't go  
for the green,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brigitte was smiling and happy, as was her husband, despite  
losing the opportunity of a career in which the 1993 Roma Masters 
was his only win. Only his caddy was mad, with the two exchanging a 
few words. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't have to focus on the bad things that happened,'' Van  
de Velde said. ``There's a lot of good things that happened this 
week, too. Besides, who will remember any of this in 200 years?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
