<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delay Placed JFK Jr. at Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The sky was hazy and growing dark when John F.  
Kennedy Jr. set out over the sea in his small plane -- conditions 
that would have made it difficult for even the most veteran pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	According to at least one family friend, it wasn't supposed to  
happen that way. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy had intended to make a daytime flight Friday but was  
delayed when his sister-in-law couldn't leave work early enough and 
he hit traffic coming out of New York, the friend, speaking on 
condition of anonymity, told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	For a relatively inexperienced pilot like Kennedy, without the  
training to rely solely on instruments in bad weather, it may have 
been an ill-advised idea to set out as darkness fell, many flight 
experts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pointing toward open ocean on a nearly moonless night, that  
has tripped up pilots for a long, long time,'' said Drew Steketee, 
senior vice president of the Aircraft Owners and Pilots 
Association. ``Flying at night requires more vigilance. Flying at 
night over ocean, the risks go up more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the investigation has only begun, and there is no  
indication that the crash resulted from poor training or 
decision-making by Kennedy. Crashes can also result from mechanical 
failure, fuel problems or other factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Aboard the plane with Kennedy were his wife, Carolyn Bessette  
Kennedy, and her sister Lauren Bessette, a New York investment 
banker. 
</P>
<P>
	No flight plan was filed to detail Kennedy's route to the island  
of Martha's Vineyard, and he did not request air traffic control 
assistance along the way. Flying without a flight plan or radar 
assistance isn't unusual for flights conducted under ``visual 
flight rules'' -- flights that take place in good weather, with the 
pilot keeping track of his own position and nearby aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	What was known is that he left Fairfield, N.J., at 8:38 p.m.  
Friday with visibility reported at 4 to 5 miles. His flight path 
took him over the Connecticut shore, and after passing over the 
southwestern tip of Rhode Island at 9:26 p.m., the plane headed 
toward Martha's Vineyard, said Robert Pearce, chief investigator 
for the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane was at 5,600 feet when it headed out over the ocean.  
At 9:40 p.m., about 17 to 18 miles west of Martha's Vineyard, it 
was at 2,500 feet. When it was last detected, 29 seconds later, it 
was at 1,800 feet, about 16 1/2 miles west of the Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's pretty far out to be that low,'' said Michael Barr,  
director of the aviation safety program at the University of 
Southern California and an experienced fighter pilot. ``Most likely 
it was one continuous descent after that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Kennedy's craft could handle such a rapid a descent if  
flown under control, Barr said planes of that type usually descend 
at half that rate. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service reported that haze cut visibility  
to about 6 miles at the Martha's Vineyard Airport, where he was 
supposed to drop off Lauren Bessette and then head for Cape Cod for 
the wedding of his cousin Rory Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was clear. They were definitely landing visually (without  
instruments),'' said Adam Budd, a ramp attendant working on the 
Martha's Vineyard Airport runway when Kennedy's plane was expected. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dr. Bob Arnot, chief medical correspondent for NBC, said  
visibility that night was limited by haze as he passed about 3 
miles south of the Vineyard just after 9 p.m. He had to rely on 
instruments to land at the nearby island of Nantucket, where he 
vacations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just black,'' Arnot said. ``You couldn't see Martha's  
Vineyard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instruments include devices to locate airports, to maintain  
specific courses and speeds and to find the correct direction and 
angle to specific runways. 
</P>
<P>
	Even for experienced pilots, flying at night over ocean is a  
tricky proposition. 
</P>
<P>
	``He set himself up into a very bad corner by flying over the  
ocean at sunset, in the haze,'' Barr said. ``I always said it's 
like flying in an eggshell, everything just blended together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At night, over water, with just a sliver of moon, the horizon  
can be impossible to see. 
</P>
<P>
	``In layman's language, you can't tell which way is up,''  
Steketee said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to newspaper reports, Kennedy, 38, had flown 100 to  
200 hours since getting his license. When he passed his pilot's 
exam 15 months ago, Kennedy had 92 hours of flight time -- more than 
double the 40 hours most test takers have, said John McColgan, a 
Federal Aviation Administration examiner who tested Kennedy after 
he took a pilot's course at the Flight Safety Academy in Vero 
Beach, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	He passed with flying colors, McColgan said, and was licensed to  
fly by visual flight rules. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
