<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> JFK Jr. Search Anything But Routine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Kennedy family wanted to keep it relatively  
routine. But the search for the single-engine plane that 
disappeared over the Atlantic with John F. Kennedy Jr. inside was 
anything but that. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House ``situation room'' was alerted. Federal  
transportation officials swung into action, and sophisticated 
military equipment was brought to the waters off Martha's Vineyard. 
Several Clinton administration cabinet members, including the 
secretary of defense, were rousted from their beds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The same amount of effort would have been expended for an  
average citizen,'' said Capt. Sandy Troeber of the Air Force's 
rescue coordination center in Virginia. ``Every life is as 
important as the next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Coast Guard says it has ``no set protocol'' -- no  
benchmark on how to react when a civilian's small plane vanishes or 
goes down. ``Every case is different,'' said Petty Officer Virginia 
Adams. ``I can't give you a specific.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The search for Kennedy, his wife and her sister, last seen  
departing New Jersey for the Vineyard on Friday night, began when 
the Coast Guard received a call from a family friend saying the 
plane was late. 
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guard officials called the FAA and the Air Force Rescue  
Coordination Center at Langley Air Force Base in Hampton, Va., the 
unit that coordinates searches throughout the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force notified the White House at about 5 a.m., and some  
Cabinet members -- including the transportation and defense 
secretaries -- were alerted, said White House spokesman Jake 
Siewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Within hours, a Coast Guard jet and two Coast Guard helicopters  
were launched and an Air Force plane was transformed into an aerial 
command post. Soon, 15 more small planes manned by volunteers from 
the Civil Air Patrol, the Air Force auxiliary organization, were 
dispatched to help. 
</P>
<P>
	By mid-Saturday, more than a dozen Coast Guard vessels had  
joined the search, along with Civil Air Patrols from six states. 
</P>
<P>
	Several sophisticated federal research vessels capable of  
undersea searches sailed to the scene from Montauk, N.Y., including 
one that surveys the ocean floor for the National Oceanic and 
Atmospheric Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	After night fell Saturday, Air National Guard helicopters  
equipped with infrared temperature sensors continued searching in 
the dark. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton called a Boston Coast Guard command center  
Saturday night and was ``very concerned,'' said Coast Guard Rear 
Adm. Richard Larrabee, who spoke Sunday to Massachusetts Gov. Paul 
Cellucci about the search. 
</P>
<P>
	The family is communicating with government officials through  
Housing and Urban Affairs Secretary Andrew Cuomo, who is married to 
Kerry Kennedy, JFK Jr.'s cousin. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the head of the National Transportation Safety Board  
was flown to Massachusetts to set up a headquarters for the 
investigation and a command post was set up at Otis Air Force Base 
on Cape Cod to coordinate activities by the Coast Guard, Navy, 
NTSB, NOAA, Federal Aviation Administration and state agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerned about receiving preferential treatment, the Kennedy  
family had asked the government to keep its reaction relatively 
routine, government sources told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Some involved in the search bristled at the suggestion that the  
Kennedys were getting extra attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have been asking me that all day,'' said Lt. Col. Don  
Desfosse, an Air Force auxiliary pilot who spent Sunday patrolling 
the air west of the Vineyard. ``I'm out there to find somebody, and 
hopefully to find them and save them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is difficult to find a similar situation to use as a  
benchmark. In June 1997, when a helicopter carrying four Coast 
Guard crewmen crashed off the California coast, an around-the-clock 
search was called off after four days. The search involved four 
cutters, a helicopter and a plane. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
