<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fight for Control of Phone Cos. Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two rival telecommunications companies ended  
their five-week takeover fight for control of U S West Inc. and 
Frontier Corp. with each declaring victory. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West, a Denver-based local phone company, will merge with  
Qwest Communications International Inc. in a stock swap worth $34.7 
billion, or $69 a share, while Frontier Corp., a Rochester, 
N.Y.-based local and long-distance company, will be acquired by 
Global Crossing Ltd. for $10.9 billion, or $63 a share, in stock, 
the companies announced Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Qwest and Global Crossing are building worldwide  
fiber-optic cable networks to give customers high-speed Internet 
access. The rivals both wanted the customers and revenues of U S 
West and Frontier to make their networks profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing this whole episode will do is educate people,  
investors that yes, it's wonderful to have a state-of-the-art, 
almost science-fiction quality network, but you need customers on 
that,'' said Peter Treadway, an analyst with Ryan, Beck-Southeast 
Research Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing had formed deals with U S West and Frontier, but  
Qwest trumped them with higher offers. 
</P>
<P>
	For both Qwest and Global Crossing to declare victory, each  
company had to compromise. Qwest withdrew its bid for Frontier, and 
Global Crossing reduced the breakup fee U S West had to pay for 
backing out of its deal. U S West will now pay a $420 million 
penalty, instead of $850 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frontier is worth a lot more to Global Crossing than it is to  
Qwest,'' Treadway said. ``Frontier provides Global Crossing with a 
nationwide fiber-optic backbone, which Qwest already has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Global Crossing wasn't prepared to escalate the bidding war  
for U S West. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to shareholders, Bob Annunziata, chief executive  
officer of Global Crossing, said he would not raise his offer for U 
S West. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not believe your best interests would be served by  
increasing our bid by an additional premium of approximately $5 
billion in order to match or exceed the competing offer,'' he 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Clayton, chairman and chief executive officer of  
Frontier, will become a vice chairman of Global Crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts and investors have raised the possibility that  
Qwest only bid for Frontier as a cutthroat bargaining ploy. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could easily draw the conclusion that Qwest's bid from day  
one had a diversionary element to it,'' Treadway said. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's chairman and chief executive officer, Joseph Nacchio,  
maintains that its offer was in earnest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was interested, I was sincere, my shareholders, to be  
perfectly frank weren't all that interested in Frontier,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's stock has been hammered since the company announced its  
offers for the two companies. The shares closed Friday at $35 a 
share, off 22 percent from its pre-bid price. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest now gets U S West's customers in 14 west and midwest  
states. The combined company will keep the Qwest name, but both 
companies will have equal representation on the 14-member board of 
directors. The combined company will pay a 5 cent annual dividend. 
U S West currently pays $2.16 a year, while Qwest pays none. 
</P>
<P>
	Because Qwest and U S West are both based in Denver, the  
companies should be able to save more money but cutting additional 
costs. And while Colorado politicians supported a Qwest-U S West 
combination, which would keep the headquarters in the state, the 
labor union has voiced opposition fearing the companies will slash 
more jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Nacchio said, ``I expect a minimal impact on the employee  
base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Executives expect the deal to close in mid-2000, pending  
regulatory and shareholder approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon Trujillo, chairman, president and chief executive  
officer of U S West will become a co-chairman of Qwest and 
president of the combined company's Internet, local and wireless 
businesses. That position is better than the vice-chairman's seat 
he was originally offered. 
</P>
<P>
	Nacchio will keep the titles of chairman and chief executive  
officer of Qwest. So, while structured as a merger of equals, 
Nacchio will have the upper hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very clear when you think about operating the company  
you've got to have one person in charge of how the business is run, 
and that person is Joe,'' Trujillo said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
